<FIRST>u a AM-JustSweatsProbe     02-04 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Just Sweats Probe,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor, Clothing Chain Founders Charged With Murder In Insurance
Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the Just Sweats clothing chain,
his partner and a doctor were charged with murder Friday in an
alleged $1.5 million insurance scam involving the faked death of the
owner.
   Melvin Hanson, co-founder of the Columbus, Ohio-based athletic
clothing chain; his partner, John Barrett Hawkins; and Dr. Richard
Pryde Boggs of Glendale were charged in the murder of Ellis Henry
Greene, 32.
   Green's body was found in Boggs' office April 16 and was
misidentified as that of Hanson.
   Hanson, 47, who was arrested last week carrying Greene's driver's
license, is being held in a Columbus, Ohio, jail on grand theft
charges under a $5 million bond. Hawkins, 25, who collected $1
million in death benefits on Hanson, remains at large. Boggs, 56,
was arrested Friday and held without bail pending arraignment Monday.
   Hanson was believed dead until mid-1988, when police in
California discovered that a man identified as Hanson who died in
Boggs' office was not Hanson.
   The discovery and the fact that Hawkins had cashed $1 million in
life insurance checks prompted authorities to file federal warrants
for their arrest.
   Authorities allege that Hanson's death was faked to collect the
insurance money.
   The murder charges against all three men carry special
circumstances that make them eligible for the death penalty. The
special circumstances alleged are murder for financial gain and
aiding and abetting.
   Ten charges were filed against each man, including murder,
conspiracy to commit murder, insurance fraud, grand theft, and
assault with a stun gun.
   Boggs, 56, told police he believed the man found dead in his
office was Hanson. He said the man died after complaining of chest
pains. Hawkins had the body cremated the next day.
   Police later discovered that a thumbprint from the corpse did not
match the one on Hanson's California driver's license. The body,
which resembled Hanson, later was identified as Greene, a former
Ohioan who lived in California.
   Hanson and Hawkins also are accused of stealing about $2 million
from Just Sweats, which they founded in 1985. The company has filed
for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
bankruptcy code.
</TEXT>
