<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Coach-Guns     02-04 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coach-Guns,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Football Coach Suspended Over Use Of Guns In Team Photo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXON HILL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head coach of a high school football
team was suspended for allegedly staging a photo session on school
grounds in which some of his players posed with a machine pistol, an
assault rifle and a bayonet, school officials said.
   Mike Pearson, a physical education teacher at Oxon Hill High
School in Prince George's County, Md. was placed on administrative
leave with pay on Monday after school officials learned that
defensive players on the school's football team posed, weapons in
hand, for the promotional poster on Jan. 27.
   A student told school officials that Pearson asked him to bring
the weapons to school, officials said Friday. The weapons were not
loaded when they were confiscated by school security officers and
turned over to police, school officials said.
   The student, who is enrolled at the school but is not a member of
the Oxon Hill football team, was temporarily suspended Monday,
school officials said.
   The players said the poster was intended to be used as a
publicity stunt to showcase the team's ``top guns'' and originally
was supposed to be staged at the county jail.
   That didn't work out, so they staged the photo session at the
school.
   ``It was a pretty innocent thing,'' one player, who asked not to
be identified, told The Washington Post. ``The idea was to make the
guys look tough, that's all.''
   The incident occurred one day after four students were shot at
another high school in nearby Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
