<FIRST>r w PM-Eastern-Trump     02-04 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Trump,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Needs Only FAA Approval to Take Over Eastern Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump needs only a safety certification
from the Federal Aviation Administration to clear the way for his
takeover of Eastern Airlines' profitable Northeastern shuttle
service.
   The Transportation Department declared his organization
financially fit Friday, giving final approval of an economic
certification for the New York real estate magnate.
   The department had given tentative approval of the planned $365
million purchase two weeks ago and it became final after no
objections were raised by interested parties, said department
spokesman Hal Paris.
   ``As far as we're concerned, he can fly,'' said Paris. He said
the department determined that Trump had the managerial talent and
the financial resources to operate what is to be renamed the Trump
Shuttle.
   FAA spokesman John Leyden said there is no deadline for issuing
an operating certificate but it could be approved within the month.
Trump had said he wanted to begin the service under his name this
month.
   Leyden said the FAA has to determine whether Trump has the
ability to run a safe airline by examining all his plans, including
pilot training, maintenance and operating procedures.
   Once the FAA gives its approval, the sale by Texas Air Corp.,
Eastern's Houston-based holding company, can become final and Trump
can repaint the shuttle's 17 Boeing 727 jetliners with his name and
gold, red and black stripes.
   Texas Air has been trying to sell off the Shuttle and some other
Eastern assets, arguing that it needs cash for Eastern to survive.
   A federal judge approved the sale last December over objections
from labor leaders who said it was part of a Texas Air effort to
dismantle Eastern and reconstruct it as a nonunion company.
   Judge Barrington D. Parker, in his opinion, recognized the
union-management struggle but said it was also plausible that the
company was trying to rebuild and place itself on sound financial
footing.
   The union has said it would appeal the decision.
   Trump already owns a helicopter service that flies between
Atlantic City, where he owns casinos, and New York City, where he
has built up a real estate empire. He announced an agreement to
purchase the shuttle service last October.
   Eastern says the shuttle, which employs 850 people and makes 62
flights a day, made average annual profits of $17 million over the
last five years while the airline itself lost $233.7 million in the
first nine months of 1988.
   Trump has vowed to recognize unions representing pilots, flight
attendants and mechanics but has not guaranteed current wages.
Eastern has offered to retain any shuttle workers who wish to remain
with the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
