<FIRST>u a AM-JALCrashAward     02-04 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-JAL Crash Award,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Italian Family $1.5 Million In JAL Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state jury on Friday ordered Boeing Co. to pay
$1.5 million in damages to the family of an Italian man and his son
who were among the 520 people who died in the 1985 crash of a Japan
Air Lines Boeing 747 in Japan.
   Attorneys for the Italian widow, Heidi Moroni, 48, and her
18-year-old son, Alessandro, had sought more than $6 million in
damages from the Seattle-based airplane company, said Boeing lawyer
Tom McLaughlin.
   Killed were Giancarlo Moroni and a second son, Andrea Moroni.
   Boeing has admitted liability in the crash, saying improper
repairs it made after the plane scraped its tail during a hard
landing in 1978 were to blame.
   The King County Superior Court jurors deliberated a day and a
half before returning their decision.
   The amount of damages was the only issue to be decided in the
Moroni case and three others, all involving non-Japanese victims,
that are pending in King County.
   Damage suits filed on behalf of 71 Japanese nationals against
Boeing and Japan Air Lines have been moved to Japan for trial.
   According to Japanese press reports last month, there have been
out-of-court settlements with families of 377 of the crash victims.
   McLaughlin described the award as ``reasonable,'' and said the
only portion Boeing might challenge is $200,000 for the suffering
endured by the two in the half-hour the damaged plane remained aloft
before it crashed into a mountain.
   The plane lost its tail and rudder 12 minutes after takeoff, and
over the next half-hour the pilot fought to regain control of the
crippled jet. Four survived the crash.
</TEXT>
