<SECOND>PM-BRF--Computer Virus-Cornell,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cornell Completes Probe of Student Suspected of Creating Computer
Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cornell University has completed its
investigation of the graduate student suspected of starting a
computer virus that clogged 6,000 computers nationwide in November,
a school official said.
   The university will not make its findings public until the report
is actually completed during the next few weeks, M. Stuart Lynn,
vice president for Information Technologies at Cornell and a member
of the investigative panel, said Friday.
   The student, Robert T. Morris, 23, is on indefinite leave from
the university while federal officials ponder what charges he will
face in connection with the Nov. 2 incident.
   Authorities accuse Morris of developing the virus that replicated
itself nationwide in computers using the Defense Department's
ARPANET computer network. Federal authorities are reportedly
undecided about whether to charge Morris with a felony or
misdemeanor.
