<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EPAConsultants     02-04 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA Consultants,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say Consult Arrangement Promotes Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Environmental Protection Agency wanted
to prepare an annual report to Congress on its Superfund toxic waste
cleanup program, it sought out a consultant.
   ICF Inc. prepared the document for $260,000. Congressional
critics maintain that little more than the letterhead was changed on
the draft received from the private company before it was sent to
Capitol Hill.
   ``Three words were changed, two `ands' and a `the','' complained
Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., who held a hearing Friday on the
widespread use of private consultants by the federal agency
responsible for cleaning up the environment.
   He said one of his major concerns is that many of the consultants
working for the EPA ``also have private sector clients from the very
industries the EPA is charged with regulating'' raising questions
about conflict of interest.
   Pryor and other critics suggested that the EPA _ and most likely
other federal agencies and departments as well _ are relying too
heavily on private contractors to do work, including critical
analysis and often decision-making, that the government ought to be
doing.
   EPA officials acknowledged in testimony before Pryor's Government
Affairs subcommittee that they make extensive use of consultants,
but maintained that precautions are taken to avoid a conflict of
interest. They insisted that decision-making remains in agency hands.
   ``It comes down to workload. It's a matter of resources,'' Henry
Longest, director of the EPA's Superfund cleanup program, where
contractors are used widely, told the Senate panel.
   But Pryor, who has waged a decade-long fight against the federal
government's extensive use of private consultants, did not accept
the explanation.
   ``Consultants do everything from working on enforcing compliance
with EPA regulations to writing EPA's annual reports,'' Pryor
declared in opening the hearing. ``It appears that the basic work of
EPA has been delegated to private consultants.''
   The senator cited the case of a Florida subcontractor found by
congressional investigators to have recommended a particular cleanup
method for a toxic waste dump. It turned out that the same company
owned the rights for that cleanup method and was given the job, said
Pryor.
   Pryor also cited the EPA contracts with ICF Inc., including the
one for preparing the agency's annual report to Congress on
Superfund, as another example where questions of conflict of
interest might be raised.
   While ICF Inc., has several so-called ``sliding'' contracts with
the EPA valued for as much as $15 million, it also aggressively
seeks business with private companies that are subject to EPA
regulation and ``boasts of its EPA connection in its promotional
literature,'' said Pryor.
   Earlier this week the Office of Technology Assessment, which is
Congress' scientific research agency, also criticized the EPA for
relying too much on contractors in its Superfund cleanup program,
suggesting that contractors and not EPA officials are running the
program.
   Superfund is the $8.5 billion program through which the EPA is
tackling hundreds of toxic waste cleanup projects across the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
