<FIRST>r a PM-SyringeShortage     02-04 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Syringe Shortage,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shortage of Disposable Syringes Delays Oregon AIDS Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program to help prevent the spread of
AIDS among intravenous drug abusers by distributing free sterile
needles has been delayed due to a shortage of disposable syringes,
organizers said.
   The sponsoring agencies, Portland-based Outside In and the
American Foundation for AIDS Research, had planned for the program
to begin in July but had difficulty insuring the program.
   The groups found a company in November to provide medical
liability insurance, but National Union Fire Insurance Co.
stipulated that the distributed needles must be of such a design
that they could not be re-used.
   Outside In has been negotiating with a British company to supply
single-use hypodermic syringes, agency director Kathy Oliver said
Wednesday. Delivery had been promised Jan. 1, but the manufacturer
can't mass produce them, she said.
   Oliver said the supplier is having 1,500 syringes manufactured
each month. Outside In will need a couple of thousand each month for
its distribution program, she said.
   She said she didn't know when the supply problem would be
resolved.
   Epidemiologists have said that direct blood contamination through
shared needles is the most rapid way acquired immune deficiency
syndrome is being spread.
</TEXT>
