<FIRST>r w PM-US-Japan     02-04 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Promises to Work on Opening Japanese Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says U.S.-Japanese relations
entail ``some confrontation at times'' and vows to make sure that
American businesses gain fair access to markets in that nation.
   Bush spoke Friday at a White House luncheon for U.S. business
leaders as Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita wrapped up a
two-day visit to Washington.
   Takeshita was leaving Friday night for Los Angeles and a meeting
there next week with former President Reagan.
   Speaking of the barriers U.S. companies face entering Japanese
markets, Bush pledged ``to do my level best ... to be sure that we
are treated fairly, that we have access, that we ... are not
operating under standards that favor one side to the detriment of
the other.''
   Bush observed that he and Takeshita ``are realistic men ... and
we realize we are going to have some confrontation at times, or
certainly differences of opinion.''
   The president added that he believes the prime minister ``wants
very much to have a cooperative relationship.''
   On Thursday, the two men pledged after their 2{-hour meeting and
lunch to strive to smooth irritations over the $50 billion U.S.
deficit with Japan and tensions over the Japanese contributions to
its defense effort.
   Bush did not elaborate on the details of the trade problems he
and the prime minister discussed on Thursday, but said they'd
``reviewed the progress that our nations have achieved in bringing
the economies into better balance and of further opening our markets
to each other's goods and services.''
   He added that the United States carries ``a disproportionate
responsibility for the defense requirements of free countries'' and
Japan, ``given its economic standing today, is willing to accept
much more in the way of responsibility for helping ... in the whole
development aid side of things.''
   ``I just wanted to assure you that the visit yesterday had gone
reasonably well,'' Bush told the businessmen.
   As the president spoke, Secretary of State James A. Baker III bid
Takeshita a formal farewell at the end of his two-day Washington
visit with a State Department luncheon of champagne toasts, pheasant
and ice cream with mangoes.
   In remarks at the luncheon, the secretary of state also struck a
cautionary note, telling Takeshita the two economic superpowers
``still face a difficult agenda.'' Baker also expressed hope the
partnership will grow stronger as Japan assumes a broader world role.
   ``Japan is determined to do its utmost to collaborate with the
United States, its strongest ally, for the peace and security of the
world,'' the prime minister said, in his toast.
   ``No problems are unsolvable as long as Japan and the United
States join in an effort to solve them,'' Takeshita said.
</TEXT>
