<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AntarcticaShipwreck     02-04 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antarctica Shipwreck,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Damage Grows From Antarctica Fuel Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birds and other wildlife in one of the most
remote parts of the world are being injured and killed by fuel oil
spilled from a ship wrecked on an Antarctica island, and more damage
is possible before cleanup crews arrive.
   Biologist Ted De Laca, chief scientist at Palmer Station in
Antarctica, said that more than 24,000 penguins and other birds are
endangered by an oil spill that threatens to wipe an entire
generation of chicks maturing in nests surrounded by the pollution.
Some wildlife already has been killed, he said.
   ``The environment has been compromised in a way that we can't
even evaluate right now,'' De Laca said in a telephone conference
call from Palmer Station. ``It's very disturbing. Everything right
now is worrisome.''
   Palmer Station scientists, wearing respirators to protect against
the eye-stinging fumes of the oil slick, worked in open boats to
recover debris littering the fouled bay and to evaluate the damage.
   But De Laca said a more effective effort to contain the spill
must await the arrival Monday of a Navy oil pollution control team
from the United States.
   He said the fuel oil is spilling from the Argentine ship Bahia
Paraiso at the rate of about two gallons a minute and if it
continues the vessel could dump about 250,000 gallons into the
previously pure, untainted waters nearby.
   The ship, which doubled as a cruise ship and a supply vessel for
an Argentine research station, ran aground near Palmer Station last
Saturday. It later floated free, went aground again 1.1 miles from
the U.S. outpost and then turned over on its right side against
another island. As it turned, fuel oil and deck cargo spilled into
the Palmer Station embayment, home to a number of large bird
rookeries.
   Palmer Station is a National Science Foundation research station.
Twenty-six scientists and staff are now working at the station under
the director of De Laca, the chief scientist. Palmer is about 600
miles south of Cape Horn, the tip of South America.
   De Laca reported that krill, a tiny shrimp-like crustacean, have
been killed by the thousands and are lining the nearby beaches.
Birds feeding on the krill seem sickened, he said. In a nesting area
of the Polar Skua, a bird of prey, up to 40 percent of the chicks
have disappeared, possibily because parent birds sickened by the oil
are unable to protect their young, he said.
   About 24,000 penguins nest in rookies in the affected area, and
De Laca said that 38 of 40 adult birds checked by scientists have
been ``fuel dipped.''
   A number of seals were seen to be covered with oil and were
acting in a ``lethargic fashion,'' said the scientist.
   The precise number of animals killed by the oil is difficult to
calculate because other animals quickly eat the dead. ``It's pretty
depressing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
