<DOCNO> AP890204-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0201EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     02-04 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0986</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royalty watchers who couldn't get enough of
Princess Diana's visit to New York can catch a glimpse of Princess
Anne when she comes to the United States for the 1989 Volvo World
Cup equestrian competition.
   Buckingham Palace confirmed Thursday that the 38-year-old
princess, fourth in line to the British throne, will visit the
competition. It will be held April 12-16 at the Florida State
Fairgrounds' Bob Thomas Equestrian Center.
   According to Winkie Howell, a member of Tampa's World Cup
Committee, the princess usually appears at the finals. He said her
anticipated visit ``points up the magnitude of the World Cup to
people who are not familiar with it.''
   As many as 160,000 people are expected to attend the equestrian
festival, which will be broadcast live by satellite to 250 million
people worldwide.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Ray Charles says he prefers the
song ``America the Beautiful'' over ``The Star-Spangled Banner''
because it's easier to sing and more graphic.
   Charles, commenting in the Broadcast Music Inc. publication Music
World, said the range of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' extends an
octave and a fifth.
   ``Few people can reach both ends with comfort,'' he said in the
winter issue of the publication. Additionally, he described the
lyrics as bombastic.
   Charles, who has recorded a well-known version of ``America the
Beautiful,'' asked,``Honestly, wouldn't you rather sing about the
beauty of America?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEDMINSTER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publishing magnate Malcolm Forbes is the
new owner of a 1749 document that is believed to be one of the last
remaining royal charters in New Jersey.
   Forbes, who collects rare documents and purchased the Bedminster
township charter from a private collector, said Thursday he will
display the charter in a climate-controlled case at his New Jersey
office building. The document was originally given to Bedminster
Township by King George II of Great Britain.
   Bedminster Mayor Joseph Cirona said the asking price for the
charter was $20,000 to $25,000, but the purchase price was not
disclosed.
   The document was believed lost in an 1845 fire that destroyed the
home of a town clerk who stored it in a desk. But in 1918, the
Somerset County Historical Quarterly revealed that the document had
somehow survived.
   Forbes' son Christopher said the relic is one of the last
remaining royal charters in the state. He said it grants Bedminster
the right ``to be and remain a perpetual township and community in
word and in deed, to be called and known by the name of the Township
of Bedminster.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Moody's week didn't exactly follow the
classic lines of a Hollywood script, but it did have a kind of happy
ending.
   The man who portrayed a teacher at the High School of Performing
Arts in the 1980 movie ``Fame'' lost and then regained his real-life
job as a drama teacher at the school for aspiring actors and dancers.
   He holds a temporary teaching certificate and was told Wednesday
he was being replaced by a drama teacher with a permanent license
and more seniority.
   But on Friday the United Federation of Teachers announced that an
agreement had been reached with the Board of Education for Moody to
remain in the drama class and team-teach with his replacement, said
union spokesman Bert Shanas.
   Team-teaching puts more than one teacher in the same classroom
and takes advantage of each teacher's special skills, Shanas said.
   Moody said he chose to teach with a temporary license because it
meant he could take acting jobs. He has appeared in eight movies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet human rights activist Andrei Sakharov is
planning another visit to Boston, this time with his wife, Yelena
Bonner, friends and family members said.
   The Sakharovs are scheduled to fly from Moscow to Rome next week.
After five days in Italy, they plan to visit Canada and then fly to
Boston to see Mrs. Bonner's children.
   Mrs. Bonner's daughter, Tatiana Yankelevich of Newton, said
Friday the dates of the Boston visit are still uncertain.
   Although both Sakharov and Bonner have visited the United States
before, this will be their first trip here together.
   Sakharov, 67, won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his defense
of human rights in his homeland. After speaking out against the
Soviet intervention in Afghanistan in 1979, he was exiled to the
closed industrial city of Gorky, about 250 miles from Moscow.
   Mrs. Bonner was banished there as well in 1984, and the couple
remained in Gorky until Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev personally
called them back to Moscow in December 1986.
</TEXT>
