<FIRST>r i PM-Guyana-USFugitive     02-04 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guyana-US Fugitive,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Cult Leader Suffers Second Stroke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Hill, the U.S. fugitive and
jungle cult leader jailed two years ago for manslaughter, has
suffered a serious stroke, his second in three months, doctors said.
   Hill, 60, who calls himself Rabbi Edward Washington, was
transferred from prison to Georgetown Hospital earlier this week
after a stroke caused partial paralysis to his left side. A stroke
in November paralyzed his right side.
   The former leader of the now-defunct House of Israel was
convicted in Guyana in 1986 and sentenced to 20 years in jail for
ordering the killing of one of his followers, James Maion.
   Hill, whose hospital room Friday was heavily guarded by police,
is also suffering from diabetes and a heart condition. Visitors were
not allowed in to see him.
   Hill fled to this former British colony on the northeast coast of
South America in 1971 after being convicted of extortion and jumping
bail in Cleveland.
   By the early 1980s, Hill claimed a following of 10,000 and 47
``synagogues.''
   His House of Israel, which had no connection with Judaism, became
known for breaking up political opposition meetings. After the death
in 1985 of socialist President Forbes Burnham, President Desmond
Hoyte launched an investigation of the cult leading to Hill's
conviction for manslaughter.
</TEXT>
