<FIRST>r w PM-SteinbrennerPardon     02-04 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinbrenner Pardon,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Documents Say Steinbrenner's Felony Conviction a Humiliation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1974 felony conviction of New York Yankees
owner George Steinbrenner hurt his business interests and was a
source of personal humiliation, according to his successful
application for a presidential pardon.
   Former President Reagan granted the pardon just before he left
office last month.
   For example, the papers note:
   Last summer, Minnesota racing officials denied Steinbrenner an
owner's license at Canterbury Downs, the state's first parimutuel
thoroughbred racetrack, because of his conviction;
   Against his wishes, Steinbrenner declined a nomination to serve
as a member of the Board of Regents governing Florida's public
universities ``because of the adverse publicity to the Florida
educational system that would likely ensue.''
   And he has suffered the indignity of being referred to in
articles as ``a convicted felon'' and the ``only convicted felon
among baseball's ownership.''
   ``The harm suffered by Mr. Steinbrenner is far more than
economic; it is a symbolic slap in the face for a man who has tried
so hard to overcome his conviction and be a good citizen,''
Steinbrenner's lawyer, former attorney general and senator William
B. Saxbe, wrote in the application.
   The documents were obtained by The Associated Press after a
special application to the Justice Department.
   Steinbrenner was pardoned Jan. 19 by Reagan, 17 years after he
attempted to ``influence and intimidate'' employees of his
shipbuilding company into lying to a grand jury about the nature of
a $100,000 contribution to Richard Nixon's 1972 re-election campaign.
   Steinbrenner pleaded guilty to conspiring to violate federal
election laws. He was fined $15,000 but received no prison sentence.
</TEXT>
