<FIRST>r w PM-Deaver     02-04 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaver,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deaver Abandons Perjury Appeal, Cites Desire to Put it Behind Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Michael K. Deaver says
he is broke and tired of being ``a captive of the system.''
   So, on Friday, he dropped the appeal of his conviction of lying
to a congressional subcommittee and a federal grand jury, saying he
wanted to ``put this period of my life behind me.''
   Deaver, a top adviser to former President Reagan and a close
friend of the former first family, said in a statement issued by his
lawyers that he was dropping the appeal ``with the firm belief that
I was not guilty of the charges of which I was convicted.''
   However, he said, ``to proceed with this appeal means to continue
to live in doubt, to continue to wait for a decision, and, if my
appeal is successful, to face another trial, a process which could
mean another two years of agony and doubt.''
   He also said he could not continue the ``financial burden'' of
the appeals process.
   The 50-year-old onetime Reagan deputy chief of staff was fined
$100,000 and ordered to perform 1,500 hours of community service for
his three felony convictions in 1987 of lying about his lobbying of
former administration colleagues after leaving the White House.
   ``My decision to withdraw my appeal does not come easily,''
Deaver said in the statement issued as his lawyers asked the
appellate court here to dismiss his appeal.
   ``It results from a number of factors, primarily my desire to put
this period of my life behind me and get on with whatever lies
ahead,'' Deaver said.
   Deaver must now begin performing the community service which U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson set as a condition of three
years of probation when he sentenced him last September. Jackson has
not yet specified what type of community service he will order.
   Deaver said his ``belief in my innocence has not changed from the
day the long and arduous proceedings against me began three years
ago.''
   Deaver resigned as deputy White House chief of staff in 1985 to
start a Washington public relations firm. He was convicted in
December 1987 of lying under oath to the House Energy and Commerce
oversight and investigations subcommittee and a grand jury.
</TEXT>
