<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Bomb     02-04 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bomb,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Of Unexploded German Bomb Prompts Evacuation Of Thousands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people were evacuated from the East End
after a large unexploded German bomb dating from World War II was
discovered at a housing site, Scotland Yard reported.
   Army bomb disposal officers called to the scene Friday worked
through the night, but the Defense Ministry said in a statement it
could take two days to render the 1,000-pound bomb harmless.
   The statement said the explosives would have to be steamed out of
the bomb because it was considered too dangerous to try to transport
the bomb from the area.
   The bomb was found standing upright against a wall in
Whitechapel, haunt of the notorious murderer Jack the Ripper, who
killed five women in 1888 and was never caught.
   It was unearthed by a mechanical digger driven by Edward
Thornton, who was digging excavations for new houses.
   Bombs dropped during the war that failed to go off are
periodically unearthed in London. The East End was especially
heavily bombed by the Germans during the war in a bid to cripple the
London docks.
   Police cordoned off the area and authorities evacuated people
from their homes around the Sidney Street housing project.
   Those evacuated stayed with friends and relatives or at local
council offices that were hurridly turned into temporary shelters.
   Twenty roads into the area also were closed to traffic.
</TEXT>
