<FIRST>r w PM-RJR-KKRMerger     02-04 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR-KKR Merger,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Hinges on Ketchup, Nuts and Chinese Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest leveraged buyout now
depends on which of the two corporations involved makes the best
ketchup, nuts and Chinese food.
   In a decision announced Friday, the Federal Trade Commission said
it would not challenge the $24.5 billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco
by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. if KKR within a year sells:
   _The Chun King oriental line of RJR Nabisco or the La Choy line
of Beatrice-Hunt-Wesson Inc., a unit of KKR.
   _The Planters nuts line of RJR Nabisco or the Fisher nuts line of
Beatrice.
   _And RJR Nabisco's Del Monte ketchup or Beatrice's Hunt ketchup.
   Together, the corporations account for one-eighth of the food
sold in the nation's supermarkets. The FTC said the two must reduce
their share of the markets for ketchup, oriental foods and packaged
nuts, in order for the market to remain competitive.
   A spokesman for KKR said that to his knowledge, no decisions had
been made on which product lines to keep and which to sell off.
   KKR's tender offer for RJR Nabisco shares was to expire at
midnight EST Monday, but KKR late Friday extended its offer to 10
a.m. EST Thursday. The second step of the merger process, involving
the exchange of securities not tendered to KKR, must still occur and
there is no time limit for completion of that portion of the deal.
   Under an agreement between the FTC and Kohlberg Kravis Roberts,
KKR must maintain RJR Nabisco as a separate operation until the
three product lines are sold.
   Before divestitures, the merged company would control about 12{
percent to 13 percent of the market for manufactured foods, said
Jeffrey Zuckerman, head of the commission's Bureau of Competition.
   Zuckerman declined to give estimates of market share held by each
of the lines but did give these estimates if the brands were
combined: Chun King-La Choy, ``probably slightly under 60 percent''
of $300 million in sales; Del Monte-Hunt ketchup, about 25 percent
of $500 million; and Planters-Fisher nuts, ``about 50 percent'' of
$1.5 billion.
   Although market share is a concern, ``we look at other factors,
the most important of which is the ease with which other people
could enter the business'' if the company tried to raise prices, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
