<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EthicsChief     02-04 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics Chief,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Chief Served Dual Role, Paper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Counsel and chief ethics adviser C.
Boyden Gray says he will continue to serve as chairman of his
family's large communications company but will give up the fee he
collected during his eight previous years as vice presidential
counsel, a published report says.
   The Washington Post also reported today that Gray was a very
active investor during those eight years, moving hundreds of
thousands of dollars annually in and out of the stock market and
various partnerships, including real estate, oil and gas,
electronic, computer and other high-tech companies.
   The Associated Press could not reach Gray at his home Friday
night.
   The Post said Gray told the paper Friday that in order to conform
with new ethics guidelines pledged by Bush, he will no longer accept
a fee from the family company, Summit Communications Inc. of Atlanta
which was founded by his father in 1948.
   He told the Post he has reduced his holdings to real estate
partnerships, government bonds and a multimillion-dollar interest in
Media General Corp., another communications giant.
   However, Gray said he does not see any need to further divest
himself or create a blind trust for his remaining investments, as
members of the Bush administration have been encouraged to do.
   Gray's past participation in the management of his investments,
currently estimated at $10 million, was reported as required on
government disclosure statements and did not violate the law.
   Gray served as general counsel to the Presidential Task Force on
Regulatory Relief, which Bush chaired, during Reagan's first term as
president.
   The panel was charged with reducing the burden of federal
regulation on private business _ a charter that theoretically could
have enabled it to affect the affairs of companies in which Gray
owned stock.
   ``I was my own ethics officer,'' Gray told the Post, adding that
he and his deputies ensured that he avoided any potential conflicts.
</TEXT>
