<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     02-04 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aide Says Nixon Would Use Extra Pension Money to Pay for Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Richard Nixon says the former
president would use the controversial proposed pay raise for members
of Congress and the Cabinet and federal judges for security.
   Responding to a request by David Keating, executive vice
president of the National Taxpayers Union for Nixon to publicly
oppose the pay increase, spokesman John H. Taylor wrote in a letter:
``The Nixons are now paying for their own security, an expense of
over $500,000 since 1985.''
   ``It is RN's intention to apply whatever increase may be enacted
in his pension entirely toward defraying the cost of his and Mrs.
Nixon's security,'' Taylor added.
   The raise which would increase Cabinet salaries from $99,500 to
$155,000 would increase Nixon's pension as a former president by the
same amount because of a 1971 law linking the two amounts.
   The pay raises automatically go into effect unless they are
disapproved by both houses of Congress before Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lujan Says Interior Still Backs Alaska Refuge Oil Exploration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly sworn Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan Jr.
says the department won't abandon its recommendation that a vast
wildlife refuge in northeastern Alaska be opened for gas and oil
exploration despite pressure from several powerful environmental
groups to review the decision.
   In his first news conference after being sworn in as interior
secretary Friday, Lujan told reporters President Bush ``has said we
should explore (the refuge) in an environmentally acceptable
manner'' and the question ``is out of my domain.''
   A recommendation endorsing development of the Alaska refuge was
sent to Congress by outgoing interior secretary Donald Hodel in the
final days of the Reagan administration.
   Congress must approve any such oil exploration, and legislation
has been introduced in both the Senate and House that would open the
refuge for drilling. But other legislation also has been introduced
that would make the refuge a wilderness area protected from
exploration.
</TEXT>
