<HEAD>IRS Commissioner Resigning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's head tax collector is resigning.
   Lawrence B. Gibbs, commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service
for 2{ years, will leave the post on March 4, spokesman Scott Waffle
announced Friday.
   Gibbs, 50, had said taxpayers should be treated by IRS employees
as customers and during his tenure launched a major drive to improve
service to taxpayers.
   He originally opposed congressional passage of a ``taxpayer bill
of rights,'' designed to protect taxpayers who are subjects of IRS
enforcement efforts, but endorsed the measure after it was amended.
   Waffle said the commissioner would not immediately disclose what
he will do after leaving the position.
