<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Defector     02-04 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Defector,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defector's Saga To Freedom In Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Soviet Jewish scientist Yakov Kogan
contacted Israeli officials in Paris last week to say he wanted to
defect, little did he know the complications he faced.
   First, he was told, ``Prove you are Jewish'' _ a serious problem
because Kogan had left his identity card thousands of miles away in
Moscow.
   What followed was a nightmarish saga of wrong airports,
problematic telephones, delays and mixed directions _ proving to
Kogan it wasn't as easy to defect as he may have thought.
   Kogan, a 48-year-old mathematician and computer expert, told the
Israeli daily Yediot Ahronot he first thought of defecting while
attending the scientific seminar as part of a six-member Soviet
delegation.
   ``I thought this was the chance to reach Israel. ... Who knows if
this opportunity would ever be repeated,'' he said in the interview
published Thursday.
   Kogan decided to phone Israeli diplomats in Paris. But the task
proved complicated.
   ``I did not want to phone from the hotel and I was looking for
public telephones. But soon I discovered you cannot use a coin for
every telephone and that for some you need a magnetic card,'' Kogan
said.
   Contact was finally established. But then came the Israeli
demand: ``Prove that you are Jewish.''
   Kogan's Soviet-issued identity card, which he left behind in
Moscow, stated he was Jewish. But the passport he carried made no
mention of his religion.
   According to Israel's Law of Return, all Jews are eligible for
automatic Israeli citizenship.
   ``They asked: `What Jewish holidays do you remember?''' Kogan
recalled. ``I told them with a stressed Yiddish accent: Rosh Hashana
(the Jewish New Year), Yom Kippur (the Day of Atonement), and of
course Shavuot (a holiday celebrating the spring harvest)'' he said.
   The officials were not immediately convinced. But the next day,
when Kogan called back, officials told him to take a taxi to Orly
Airport and go to the El Al (Israel's airline) counter.
   Kogan left all his belongings at a hotel, toured the Quai D'Orsay
museum and left for the airport. But there were more problems ahead.
   ``They only forgot to tell me that Orly is divided in two, West
and South, with the first one designated for internal flights
only,'' he told Yediot.
   When Kogan finally reached his destination, time was running out.
   ``I ... could not find the El Al counter. Then I started to walk
around slowly, and gradually saw the word `Tel Aviv' appearing on
display screens,'' the bespectacled, gray-haired Kogan said Thursday
on Israel Television.
   He said he passed through French passport control with the help
of an El Al official, who issued him an Israeli visa. Then he was
brought to an empty plane.
   ``They told me that I can relax now, that this is Israeli
territory,'' he said.
   Take-off was delayed for what seemed an endless 30 minutes, Kogan
said. Once the plane took off, he destroyed a piece of paper on
which he had written the number of his Israeli contacts in Paris, as
they had ordered.
   ``At (Tel Aviv's) Ben Gurion Airport, two men were waiting for
me. One of them asked: ``Why did you arrive alone? You could ask for
a visa and bring along your family.''
   Kogan left behind his wife, Asia, and two sons, aged 7 and 10. He
told Yediot he believed nothing would happen to them under the more
liberal policies of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He said he decided to defect because he felt progress in his
scientific career at a Moscow institute was stymied due to treatment
of Jews in the Soviet Union. He told Yediot that money played no
role _ both he and his wife were highly paid, lived in a three-room
apartment considered a luxury by Soviet standards and owned a summer
house near a forest.
   ``During all those years, I never asked to emigrate to Israel. I
knew I would be refused,'' apparently on grounds that he knew state
secrets, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
