<DOCNO> AP890204-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     02-04 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sign manufacturer Alex Goldenberg
demonstrated his product's impact in a very personal way at a trade
show by proposing to his girlfriend.
   Goldenberg typed his question into a computer Friday during the
Eastern Sign Show in this resort's Convention Center, with dozens of
clients inspecting the high-tech sign printers around him.
   His question was automatically carried to the sign printer which
then permanently embossed the message in vinyl.
   ``LANA! WILL YOU MARRY ME?'' were the words that popped up on the
screen in front of Lana Ritsman, who looked startled, then nervously
smiled.
   ``Why did you do it in front of all these people?'' she asked.
``Everybody is standing here watching us!''
   The crowd, meanwhile, waited for her response.
   A man shouted, ``Well, yes or no?''
   Ms. Ritsman, blushing, whispered ``yes'' and applause erupted.
Goldenberg placed a diamond engagement ring on her finger, and the
two kissed.
   Goldenberg, 31, and Ms. Ritsman, 21, are both from New York City.
They said they will marry in August.
   ``Oh, isn't this nice,'' a nearby saleswoman said.
</TEXT>
