<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kenya-Map     02-04 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Map,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil May Have Fueled Kenyan-Sudanese Clash Of the Cartographers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call it the Muddle of the Maps or the Clash
of the Cartographers, but Kenya and Sudan are at it again over a
disputed area of dismal swamp and desert.
   The dispute goes back years, but neither side appeared to be
paying much attention to it until recently, and a discovery of oil
may have roiled their dispute over soil.
   In 1914, the British drew a straight line marking Kenya's
northwestern border with Sudan.
   But in 1938, the British, who then ruled the East African
nations, decided to give Kenya administrative control of a
triangular piece of land north of the Sudan border.
   The area, known as the Elemi Triangle, contained 1,393 square
miles of seemingly worthless land and was home to the nomadic
Turkana tribe, which was constantly raiding and being raided by
other tribes from Sudan, Ethiopia and Uganda.
   The British administration in Khartoum, Sudan's capital, was
unable to police the raiders and handed over administration of the
area to authorities in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi, which was much
closer.
   The 1938 agreement resulted in a new line on the map, this one
putting the triangle in Kenya. There the matter rested until 1956,
when Sudan gained its independence, followed by Kenya seven years
later.
   The newly independent governments began drawing their own maps _
Sudan's with the original 1914 straight line, Kenya's with the
triangular border.
   ``From that time on,'' said Sudan's charge d'affaires in Nairobi,
Ali Yousuf, ``We have had two opinions.''
   Yousuf told reporters Friday that a joint border commission met
in the late 1970s but failed to resolve the matter, and the dispute
once again faded.
   But last year, Yousuf said, Kenya published a new map that not
only included the Elemi Triangle within its borders but enlarged the
triangle by 2,489 square miles.
   Yousuf said he called the news conference ``to clarify the
position of the Sudan government.'' He was not, he insisted,
discussing ``our borders with Kenya through the press.''
   But most of the argument has been waged through reporters.
   The newly revived dispute began with a front-page story in
Monday's Kenya Times, an English-language daily published in Nairobi
by the ruling Kenya African National Union party.
   Headlined, ``It's a Map of Provocation,'' the story noted that
thousands of maps published by a Scottish company, John Bartholomew
and Son, Ltd., of Edenburgh, showed the straight 1914 border between
Kenya and Sudan.
   The next day, the newspaper's top story carried the banner
headline, ``Sudan Claims Kenyan Soil.''
   On Wednesday, at a reception for foreign journalists, Kenya's
foreign minister, Robert Ouko, made it a point to mention the
dispute.
   He, too, said he would not discuss the matter in the press, but
added, ``The Elemi Triangle is an integral part of Kenya and that's
the way it will remain.''
   The two governments have not officially discussed the problem
anew.
   Pressed Friday at the news conference, Yousuf said he didn't
``have enough information as to who is doing what in this disputed
area,'' but suggested Kenya may have found oil in the region.
President Daniel arap Moi announced last month oil had been found in
northern Kenya, but did not specify where.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890204-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay-Cabinet     02-04 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay-Cabinet,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Cabinet Includes Possible Presidential Contender, Technocrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Paraguay, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Gen. Andres Rodriguez has
named a Cabinet made up largely of technocrats, several of whom
worked closely with ousted President Gen. Alfredo Stroessner. They
include:
   _ Army Gen. Orlando Machuca Vargas, interior. A cavalry officer
who served many years under Rodriguez, he is the only active duty
military man on the Cabinet. He will be in charge of political
affairs, including elections; and the police.
   _ Luis Maria Argana, foreign relations. A constitutional lawyer,
he served as president of the Supreme Court until resigning last
August. He is regarded by many as a potential presidential candidate
if elections are called.
   _ Juan Ramon Chaves, minister without portfolio. The 87-year-old
Colorado Party leader headed the party for 25 consecutive years
until ousted by militant Stroessner backers in August 1987. Paraguay
lacks a vice presidency and this minister fills in when the
president is absent.
   _ Antonio Zuccolillo, industry and commerce. A prosperous
businessman and industrialist, he was Stroessner's ambassador to
Britain until 1987. He is the brother of Aldo Zuccolillo, whose
newspaper ABC Color was closed by the Stroessner government in 1984.
   _ Hernando Bertoni, agriculture. An agriculture engineer and only
Cabinet member to retain his post, he is the grandson of famed Swiss
naturalist Moises Bertoni, who came to Paraguay the last century to
study its flora and fauna.
   _ Enzo de Bernardi, treasury. An engineer, he runs the state
electric company, ANDE. The son of Italian immigrants, he fought for
Italy and was decorated for bravery in World War II.
   _ Dionisio Gonzalez Torres, education. Rector of the National
University and father of navy commander Eduardo Gonzalez.
   _ Porfirio Perreira Ruiz Diaz, public works. A retired general
and mayor of Asuncion since 1976. An engineer, he launched programs
to pave streets, build bridges and improve garbage collection.
   _ Alexis Frutos Vaesken, justice and labor. A former Supreme
Court member from 1983 to 1987.
   Still to be filled are the posts of health and national defense.
</TEXT>
