<FIRST>r a PM-ChessQuarterfinals     02-04 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chess Quarterfinals,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Four Ends In Draw</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johann Hjartarson's offer of a draw after 39 moves
was accepted Friday night by Anatoly Karpov to end game four of the
World Chess Championship quarterfinals.
   With the draw, Karpov, of the Soviet Union, led Iceland's
Hjartarson, 3 to 1. Hjartarson must win the next game, scheduled for
Sunday, to stay alive in the quarterfinals six-game match.
   Grandmaster Joel Benjamin, who attended the game, said Karpov,
playing with white, ``steered into a drawish position early'' and
didn't appear interested in a win.
   He said the game appeared to be a draw most of the way. ``The
game demonstrated that if Karpov wants a draw with white, he can
have it.''
   Both players traded queens in the ninth move, which observers
said virtually assured a draw.
   Karpov, former world chess champion who is ranked second in the
world, has been the clear favorite from the start over Hjartarson,
ranked 11th in the world.
   Both players arrived late at the game site at Lakeside School in
north Seattle, because of snow on the ground and rush-hour traffic.
Nearly 200 people watched the game.
</TEXT>
