<FIRST>r a PM-JustSweatsProbe     02-04 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Just Sweats Probe,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Men Charged With Murder in Insurance Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founders of an athletic-clothing chain and
a California doctor have been charged with murder in the slaying of
a man whose death authorities say was faked to collect $1.5 million
in insurance.
   Melvin Hanson, co-founder of Just Sweats of Columbus, Ohio, his
partner, John Barrett Hawkins, and Dr. Richard Pryde Boggs of
Glendale, were charged Friday with murder, conspiracy and insurance
fraud.
   The three are accused in the death of Ellis Henry Greene, 32,
whose body was found in Boggs' office last April 16 and was
initially identified as Hanson.
   Boggs told police he believed the body was that of Hanson. He
said the man died after complaining of chest pains and Hawkins had
the body cremated the next day.
   But police later discovered that the thumb print of the corpse
did not match the one on Hanson's California driver's license. The
body subsequently was identified as Greene, a former Ohioan.
   A felony complaint issued by the Los Angeles District Attorney's
office traces the trio's activities over a three-year period. The
scheme allegedly began with Hanson's applications for multiple life
insurance policies in 1986.
   Hanson signed a will in 1987 leaving all his property to Hawkins.
Upon his death, Hanson's will directed that his body be cremated and
that none of his relatives be notified, according to court documents.
   In January 1988, the complaint said, Hanson rented a Miami
condominium using an alias and the next month consulted a plastic
surgeon about changing his appearance.
   Hanson on April 15 flew from Miami to Los Angeles, where he and
Boggs killed Greene the next day, the complaint alleges.
   Hanson left Los Angeles the same day, using the name Wolfgang Von
Snowden, and Hawkins flew to Los Angeles to claim the body
identified as Hanson's.
   Hawkins began filing claims for payments of death benefits on
Hanson two weeks later, according to the court record.
   Hanson underwent cosmetic surgery to disguise his appearance a
month after the slaying, and began using the name and identification
of the victim, Greene, as well as the name Von Snowden. Hawkins went
to Colorado, authorities said, where he used the name Jerry Anthony
Greene.
   Records of telephone calls among Hawkins, Hanson and Boggs dating
to December 1987 helped authorities uncover the alleged conspiracy.
   Hanson was arrested on Jan. 29 at Dallas-Fort Worth Airport by
U.S. Customs agents as he returned from Acapulco, Mexico.
Authorities said he was carrying identification cards under 13 names.
   Hanson appeared in court in Columbus Friday, where he was advised
that he had been charged with theft in the alleged scheme. He was
being held in the Franklin County Jail in lieu of a $5 million bond.
   Hawkins, 25, who collected $1 million in death benefits on
Hanson, remains a fugitive, authorities said.
   Boggs was being held without bail in Los Angeles and his
arraignment was scheduled for Monday afternoon.
   Hanson and Hawkins also are accused of stealing about $2 million
from Just Sweats, which they founded in 1985. The company has filed
for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of U.S. bankruptcy
laws.
   Authorities said it was unclear whether the victim was known to
any of the three men and the method by which he was killed has not
been established.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
