<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Laurel     02-04 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Laurel,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laurel Appeals To Aquino To Allow Marcos To Die At Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel said
today that an ailing Ferdinand Marcos may not survive the year and
appealed to President Corazon Aquino to allow her ousted predecessor
to die in his homeland.
   Laurel spoke to reporters after returning from Hawaii, where he
met the 71-year-old former president. He said he was told by doctors
that Marcos' heart, lungs and kidneys were failing and the former
president had lost the will to live.
   There was no immediate comment from Mrs. Aquino, who has refused
to allow her predecessor to return to the Philippines since her
February 1986 ``People Power Revolution'' ended the 20-year Marcos
regime.
   But a Manila newspaper, the Philippine Daily Inquirer, quoted a
Cabinet official as saying the government would refuse even to allow
Marcos to be buried in the Philippines.
   Presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno has said Laurel was acting
without Mrs. Aquino's blessing when he went to see Marcos.
   Relations between Mrs. Aquino and Laurel have been strained since
the vice president quit his Cabinet post as foreign minister in 1987
over policy differences. Last August, Laurel formally parted ways
with Mrs. Aquino when he demanded her resignation and announced he
was joining an opposition coalition.
   Laurel said he would try to contact Mrs. Aquino immediately to
ask for an appointment so he could relay to her Marcos's request to
come home. He would also hand Mrs. Aquino a letter from Marcos' son,
Ferdinand Jr., containing the same request.
   Asked if Marcos had offered to return part of the billions of
dollars he allegedly embezzled, Laurel replied he was ``not at
liberty to answer that.'' Later, he told another reporter no offer
was made.
   Laurel said doctors believe Marcos might not survive the trip to
the Philippines but that Marcos told him he ``doesn't mind ... and
he would be happy dying on his way home.''
   ``He told me he has already resigned his fate to Almighty God,''
Laurel said. ``Mr. Marcos expressed to me his desire to die in his
own country.''
   He said Marcos was concerned for the future of his wife, Imelda,
and three children, and added that they also should be allowed to
return.
   Before Laurel's trip, unconfirmed news reports said he and
wealthy Filipino industrialist Enrique Zobel were trying to work out
a deal under which Marcos would return part of his ``hidden wealth''
in exchange for permission to return.
   Asked how he would try to change Mrs. Aquino's mind about banning
Marcos, Laurel said that he ``will invoke the fundamental right of
any Filipino to come home ... I will try to appeal to her sense of
Christian and moral values.''
   Laurel said that his conversation with Marcos was carried on
``intermittently'' because of the former president's poor health.
Last Wednesday Marcos underwent a tracheotomy to clear fluids
building up in his lungs. He has been breathing through a respirator
since then.
   Quoting from a briefing given by doctors, Laurel said Marcos was
running a fever of 103 degrees and weighed less than 100 pounds. He
said doctors told him Marcos' lungs had collapsed twice in three
weeks, his transplanted kidneys were failing and his heart had grown
too weak to pump enough blood.
   The doctors described Marcos' body as ``now destroyed'' and said
``he has less than 10 percent chance of survivial within the year,''
Laurel said.
   Philippine officials have said in the past that Marcos must
return his allegedly embezzled funds and apologize for abuses in his
administration before there could be any discussion of his return.
   In its report, the Philippine Daily Inquirer quoted Cabinet
Secretary Jose de Jesus as saying the government would refuse Marcos
burial in the Philippines because his followers would use the
funeral to undermine Mrs. Aquino.
   Marcos and his wife are under U.S. indictment for allegedly
plundering the Philippines of more than $100 million and stashing
much of the money in the United States.
   A federal judge in New York is to decide this month if Marcos is
healthy enough to stand trial on criminal racketeering charges. Mrs.
Marcos pleaded innocent and is free on $5 million bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
