<DOCNO> AP890204-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Press     02-04 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Press,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Consider Corrections For The Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill aimed at compelling newspapers and
broadcasters to publish corrections of errors moved ahead in the
House of Commons, but legislators said it has little chance of final
success.
   The bill, introduced by opposition Labor Party lawmaker Tony
Worthington, proposes a statutory right for members of the public to
correct inaccuracies about them in the news media. Corrections would
have to be given the same prominence as the original mistake.
   Worthington said his Right of Reply bill was needed because of
what he called the ``deterioration in standards of some sections of
the press.''
   He said the bill, which was unopposed Friday in its second
reading, was not an attack on press freedom but an attack on the few
editors and proprietors who abused their power.
   Legislators said the government was neutral about the Right of
Reply Bill, so it would not have any priority on the crowded
parliamentary agenda. They said time was likely to run out before
the bill was examined in committee or in the crucial third reading.
   After being approved by the House of Commons, the bill would then
have to go to the House of Lords.
   Timothy Renton, a Home Office junior minister speaking for the
government, said scandal had been used to sell newspapers for
hundreds of years.
   ``But ... we have a number of reservations about both the
statutory control of the press and about the procedures set forth in
the bill,'' Renton said.
   Labor legislator Ann Clwyd, a journalist, said the bill was
necessary to protect the public from what she called the excesses of
the tabloid press.
   Two other bills dealing with the press failed in the House of
Commons Friday for lack of debating time.
   The Indecent Displays (Newspapers and Workplaces) bill,
introduced by Laborite Clare Short, would have barred newspapers
from publishing ``pictures of naked or partially naked women in
sexually provocative poses.''
   The Protection of Privacy bill, introduced by Conservative
lawmaker John Browne, also failed. It would have given all citizens
a legal right to privacy and compelled newspapers to show their
revelations were ``for the public benefit.''
</TEXT>
