<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HelenaExplosion     02-04 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helena Explosion,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Derailment Fire Extinguished; Residents Urged to Curtail Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents have begun cleaning up from the
debris and damage left behind by an railroad explosion and fire that
compounded the difficulties of coping with subzero cold.
   As federal officials began an investigation, many people spent
Friday sweeping up glass and assessing the destruction from the
blast, which forced 2,000 people to evacuate their homes in
temperatures of 30 below zero.
   Carroll College's 700 to 800 students remained in temporary
lodgings while hundreds of windows in dormitories and classrooms
were repaired. Classes were canceled until Feb. 13.
   Weather forecasters called for a high today of minus 22.
   The explosion early Thursday shattered windows up to two miles
away and knocked out power to half the city for more than six hours.
It was caused by 21 runaway railroad freight cars that derailed and
crashed.
   Paul Spengler, disaster coordinator for Lewis and Clark County,
said the blast site was being examined by investigators from the
National Transportation Safety Board. The Federal Railroad
Administration also has announced it will conduct a complete
investigation.
   Federal railroad officials had said the initial explosion was
caused when a derailed car hit a propane tank, but that version was
questioned Friday.
   Bill Bradford of Louis Dreyfus Propane Co. in Helena said both of
his company's propane tanks in the area were intact. The propane is
used to heat railroad switches.
   Officials said a rail tank car filled with highly flammable
hydrogen peroxide exploded just before 5 a.m., but a second hydrogen
peroxide car was quickly coated with ice from firefighters' water,
which fire crews believed minimized the danger of it exploding.
   A load of granular plastic inside one of the rail cars smoldered
until it was extinguished Friday afternoon, according to Spengler.
   Only two people were injured in the incident, neither seriously.
</TEXT>
