<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Weather Sweeps Much Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winter weather swept over much of the nation today, bringing
snow, gusty winds and frigid air that snapped low-temperature
records.
   Winter storm warnings of heavy snow with cold temperatures and
gusty winds were posted in California's Sierra Nevada and Tahoe
Valley, and parts of Nevada, Utah and Wyoming.
   Up to 3 feet of snow fell in the Sierras, with winds gusting to
more than 50 mph, creating near blizzard conditions. Up to 12 inches
of snow fell in western Nevada, including Reno and Carson City.
   Advisories for snow today extended across west-central Nevada,
northern California, southwest Oregon, southeast Idaho, central
Wyoming and much of Colorado.
   High-wind warnings were posted along Oregon's northern coast and
Washington state's Cascade Range, as well as in Southern California
and southern Nevada.
   Wind chill advisories were posted for much of Oregon, Idaho,
Montana, Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas.
   A winter weather advisory also was posted today in eastern West
Virginia.
   Low-temperature records for the date that were broken on Friday
included Des Moines, Iowa, where the 1895 record of 13 below zero
was broken by a 15-below reading.
   Record lows for today's date were broken by a 26-below reading in
Duluth, Minn., replacing the seven-year old mark of 24 below, and
Wichita Falls, Texas, where the 53-year record of 11 was supplanted
by a 10-degree reading.
   Snow continued to fall this morning in parts of Arkansas,
Missouri, Iowa, Nebraska, Kansas, Colorado, Wyoming, Idaho, Utah,
Nevada, California and Oregon. The largest accumulation for the 6
hours ending at 1 a.m. EST was 5 inches at Salt Lake City.
   Today's forecast called for snow widespread from the Sierra
Nevada through the Great Basin into the central Rockies; rain
widespread in much of California; snowshowers scattered from
southern Oregon across Nebraska into the lower Great Lakes, and
southern Iowa and northern Illinois; rainshowers scattered from the
Carolinas into the northeast Gulf Coast.
   Predicted highs: 10 below to 20 below in the northern Rockies
into Wyoming, and across northern and central Minnesota; 10 below to
zero in northwest Montana, and from the central Plains into the
northern Plains and the upper Great Lakes; 20s and 30s along the
northern Pacific Coast across the Great Basin, eastern New Mexico,
southern Texas, the lower Mississippi and Ohio valleys into southern
New England; 40s and 50s from the California coast through central
Arizona into southwest New Mexico, and from southeast Louisiana into
the Carolinas; 60s in southern Arizona; 60s and 70s across southern
Georgia and northern Florida; low 80s across southern Florida. Much
of the rest of the nation will be in the single digits and teens.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 41 degrees
below zero at Butte, Mont., to 75 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 43 cloudy; Boston 18 fair; Buffalo 13 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 60 fair; Cincinnati 22 fair; Cleveland 20 fair;
Detroit 19 partly cloudy; Miami 71 fair; New York 24 fair;
Philadelphia 22 fair; Pittsburgh 14 fair; Portland, Maine 15 cloudy;
Washington 29 wind.
   _Central: Bismarck -18 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 15 cloudy; Denver
-9 snow; Des Moines -8 snow; Indianapolis -22 fair; Kansas City -3
fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul -16 cloudy; Nashville 32 foggy; New
Orleans 44 cloudy; St. Louis 5 snow.
   _West: Albuquerque 42 cloudy; Anchorage -10 fair; Las Vegas 51
cloudy; Los Angeles 51 cloudy; Phoenix 55 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 19 snow; San Diego 55 cloudy; San Francisco 42 partly cloudy;
Seattle 7 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal -1 fair; Toronto 10 snow.
</TEXT>
