<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     02-04 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Premadasa Calls For Peace, Revolution To Eliminate Poverty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa today
called for an end to the discord tearing apart this once idyllic
island and promised a revolution to usher in social change.
   Premadasa presided over austere Independence Day celebrations _
part of a plan to save government funds for an anti-poverty program.
   ``We must terminate ethnic discord,'' he said, so that ``in the
years ahead a new revolution will flourish in every hamlet, village
and town to eliminate poverty, create an equitable social order and
eliminate discrimination.''
   Premadasa, 64, who won the Dec. 19 presidential election and took
over Jan. 2, has vowed to give monthly payments to 1.4 million
families who earn less than the national annual per capita of $360.
   After taking office, he announced a plan to pay poor people $75
monthly for two years, beginning in April. About 7 million of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people stand to gain. The president has not
specified where the funds will come from, though he has urged all
government departments to curb expenses.
   Sri Lanka's independence from Britain in 1948 was commemmorated
today by a 100-member honor guard that presented arms to the
president. Schoolgirls dressed in white sang during the ceremony in
the capital's independence square.
   The traditional military pageant and parade was absent this year,
to save money for Premadasa's anti-poverty program.
   Political analysts, however, insist the major hurdle in the
Premadasa presidency will be to curb ethnic insurgencies that have
torn the island nation apart since 1983.
   Militants from the Tamil minority, claiming discrimination by the
majority Buddhist Sinhalese, have waged a bloody insurgency for an
independent Tamil nation since 1983.
   More than 8,500 people have been killed in the 5-year separatist
insurgency by militants in the Tamil minority.
   Extremists from the Sinhalese majority, angered by the
government's peace overtures to the Tamils, have killed more than
900 people, mostly government supporters, the past 18 months.
   The government says India has begun to withdraw Indian troops
sent here in 1987 to disarm Tamils under terms of a failed peace
pact. The Indian troops are estimated at 44,000.
   Both Tamil and Sinhalese extremists have vowed to violently
disrupt parliamentary elections Feb. 15.
   Speaking in Sinhala, English and Tamil, Premadasa warned,
``Elements who seek to obstruct or destroy the democratic process
will not be tolerated by the vast majority of freedom-loving Sri
Lankans.''
   ``Let us join hands in amity and unity to make our motherland a
land of peace and prosperity,'' he said.
   The Tamils, who are mainly Hindu, make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's population. They claim discrimination by the mainly Buddhist
Sinhalese, who are 75 percent of the population and dominate the
government and military.
</TEXT>
