<FIRST>r a PM-TampaDisturbance     02-04 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tampa Disturbance,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calm Restored, But Investigation Continues in Drug Suspect's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are investigating the possibility
that a black man whose death brought about two nights of violence
might have suffocated as he was lying face down and handcuffed in a
police car.
   Edgar Allen Price, 40, of Houston, died following a struggle with
police Wednesday night as eight officers tried to arrest the
6-foot-3, 300-pound drug suspect.
   Dr. Charles Diggs, assistant Hillsborough County medical
examiner, said it appears Price suffocated.
   ``He is working it as an asphyxiated death,'' said April Strouse,
a medical investigator in the medical examiner's office. ``But we
don't know how. We have not been able to determine that yet. There
is a very intense investigation going on.''
   She said doctors hope to have conclusive results by next week.
   Diggs said officials were looking at the possibility that Price
was in the cruiser when his breathing stopped, adding that he had
been deprived of oxygen for some time.
   Price's death triggered violence Wednesday and, to a lesser
extent, Thursday night in College Hill, a poor depressed,
predominantly black neighborhood. One person was arrested Wednesday
night and nine Thursday night.
   There were no disturbances Friday night and police said that no
sections of the area were blocked off.
   The breathing of a person who is intoxicated or stunned, then
placed face down in handcuffs on a seat or car floor, can be
restricted, Diggs said. Price reportedly had alcohol in his blood.
   But Ms. Strouse, who wouldn't confirm whether tests showed Price
had been drinking, cautioned, ``There are a lot of things that can
cause restricted breathing, and we have to wait until we know for
sure.''
   Deputy Chief Thomas DePolis had said Thursday that preliminary
findings showed Price died of a cardiac arrest, but that authorities
had not yet determined what caused Price's heart to stop. The
findings showed police did not choke or beat Price during the
confrontation after an undercover crack cocaine buy, according to
Police Chief Austin McLane.
   Officials, who released the information on Price's death Thursday
in an effort to forestall more trouble, said incidents of rock- and
bottle-throwing were more sporadic and the young people fewer in
number the second night.
   City officials, residents and community leaders continued to
discuss the reasons behind the outbreak, which came less than three
weeks after three nights of unrest in Miami followed the shooting
death of a black motorcyclist. A police officer is charged in that
incident.
   ``This is not Miami, either in scope or in what touched off the
trouble,'' said John Dunn, spokesman for Mayor Sandy Freedman.
``These are teen-agers out there. This was a drug arrest that
sparked it. This was not an indiscriminate action on the part of the
police department.''
   Since an outbreak of violence in 1987 that lasted several days,
Tampa authorities have increased efforts to spruce up housing,
improve economic opportunities, and fight drug use, which they say
is an underlying problem.
   Price, a convicted felon who served 10 years in Texas on a
robbery conviction before being paroled in 1984, was carrying 25
pieces of crack cocaine and a loaded .25-caliber pistol in his
pockets, said Cole.
</TEXT>
