<FIRST>r i PM-India-Carbide     02-04 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Carbide,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhopal District Judge Orders Court Proceedings In Hindi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today struck down objections from
Union Carbide and said Hindi, not English, would be the language for
court proceedings on the 1984 gas leak that killed more than 3,300
people.
   ``Our clients do not understand Hindi,'' objected Vijay Gupta,
attorney for the Danbury, Conn.-based company. ``It will be better
if the practice of writing order sheets in English continues.''
   Bhopal District Judge N.K. Jain replied: ``The government's
clients (the gas leak victims) do not understand English.''
   The government of India is suing Union Carbide for $3 billion in
damages for the gas leak that, by the government's count, killed
3,329 people and injured more than 20,000 others.
   Jain said the two sides can argue their cases in English but the
court's order sheet that records the arguments after each hearing
will be prepared in Hindi. Up until now the arguments had been
recorded in English.
   However, he said judgments will be handed down in English.
   India filed the damage suit in 1985, but the case has bogged down
in legal wrangling in a variety of courts.
   Hindi is the official language of India, spoken by more than half
its 880 million people, especially in north and central India, where
Bhopal is located. English also is an official language.
   The Bhopal pesticide plant where the leak of methyl isocyanate
gas occurred is owned by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide Corp.
   Jain replaced Judge M.W. Deo in the case in Bhopal district judge
after the high court of Madhya Pradesh state ruled last November
that Deo was biased against Union Carbide Corp. A previous judge,
G.S. Patel, was removed for conflict of interest after it was
discovered he was among the 500,000 people who had filed claims in
an attempt to collect compensation.
   Jain set Feb. 18 as the date to fix hearing dates in the suit.
</TEXT>
