<FIRST>r a PM-TurnpikeExplosives     02-04 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turnpike Explosives,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Links Man Convicted With Explosives To Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed Japanese Red Army terrorist who was
convicted of transporting explosives was intending to use them to
blow up a Navy recruiting station in New York City, prosecutors say.
   Government attorneys, charging that Yu Kikumura has ties to a
Libyan-directed terrorist conspiracy, asked a judge Friday to
sentence him to a lengthy prison term.
   However, defense attorneys said the government's pre-sentence
report makes only ``tenuous'' ties between their client and other
terrorist incidents worldwide.
   Kikumura, 36, faces up to 100 years in prison when he is
sentenced Monday.
   In papers filed in U.S. District Court, the government revealed
that Kikumura planned to blow up a Navy recruiting station in New
York City in conjunction with a USO club bombing April 14, 1988, in
Naples, Italy.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito asked Judge Alfred J. Lechner to
help deter terrorism by sending Kikumura to prison ``at least until
he is so old that he is no longer physically capable of building and
planting bombs or assisting with terrorist plots.''
   The Naples blast came on the second anniversary of the U.S. air
strike against Libya and two days after Kikumura was arrested on the
New Jersey Turnpike with three 18-inch pipe bombs in his car.
   Each bomb, manufactured from a fire extinguisher, gunpowder and
lead shot, could destroy an average-size building, authorities said.
   Kikumura, who is alleged to be a member of the terrorist Japanese
Red Army, was arrested last April 12 and convicted Nov. 29 on
charges of illegally transporting explosives, possession of firearms
by an alien, possession of unregistered firearms and carrying false
travel documents.
   Sources have said the government believed other potential targets
may have been the United Nations building or Manhattan's garment
district.
   The pre-sentence report does not mention either site. Alito also
said a map of New York City found in Kikumura's car had marks that
indicated only the recruitment center as the target.
   The Washington Post reported Friday that the government had
evidence proving all three sites were targets of Kikumura.
   Defense attorneys Ronald Kuby and William Kunstler said in their
pre-sentence report that ``the `linkages' it (the prosecution)
attempts to make between Kikumura and others are as tenuous as they
are inflammatory.''
</TEXT>
