<FIRST>r a PM-Flight103-Families 1stLd-Writethru a0481 02-04 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Families, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Crash Victims Criticize Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs to include scholarship plan.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of some of the 259 people who
died on a Pan Am jet that crashed in Scotland are banding together
to criticize the U.S. government for its handling of the tragedy.
   Paul Hudson, a lawyer whose 16-year-old daughter, Melina, died in
the crash, said the families are ``outraged ... at the policy of
utter silence that has apparently been decided upon by the federal
government.''
   Hudson said at least a dozen family members intend to hold a news
conference Monday in New York City to discuss their criticisms. He
said the relatives believe the government should release details of
the crash investigation to them.
   Lynne Fraidowitz, whose son, Daniel Rosenthal, 20, was among the
dead, told The Syracuse Post-Standard that she would press the
government for information until ``I'm satisfied _ we're satisfied _
that we have the truth.''
   ``This is just the beginning,'' she said. ``We're not going to
let a wash go down. If we're not satisfied, we're going to do
something else. ... My son is dead. All I have is a hole in the
ground. I owe my son a reckoning.''
   Among those killed Dec. 21 were 35 students enrolled in Syracuse
University's overseas studies program. In addition to the 259 people
aboard the plane, 11 residents of Lockerbie, Scotland, also were
killed when the jet smashed into a row of houses.
   Investigators have determined that the crash was caused by a bomb
that was smuggled aboard Flight 103 in Frankfurt, West Germany. The
plane later stopped in London and was on its way to New York when
the bomb went off.
   A State Department official declined to comment on the families'
accusations, saying department officials wanted to hear the charges
at the news conference first.
   Meanwhile, a Scottish community worker has announced plans to
establish a scholarship fund that would allow Lockerbie students to
attend Syracuse. Bill Hume said the fund would be a ``living
memorial'' to the victims of the crash.
   Hume, who has arranged support services for residents of
Lockerbie since the crash, said he wants the fund to be taken from
an existing relief fund, the Lockerbie Air Disaster Appeal, which
has already raised $2.2 million.
   ``If the money could be used for something long-lasting, a living
thing where people actually exchange part of their culture and
friendship ... some happiness can come out of it,'' Hume said.
</TEXT>
