<FIRST>r i PM-Malaysia-Detainee     02-04 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia-Detainee,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Released After 11 Years In Jail Without Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today released a
carpenter who was arrested for communist activities and held for 11
years without trial, an opposition member of Parliament said.
   Cheah Swee Sam was released from the Kamunting detention camp,
120 miles north of the capital, after being held under Malaysia's
Internal Security Act, said Lee Lam Thye, secretary-general of the
opposition Democratic Action Party.
   Lee, in a statement, urged the release of other detainees held
under the act, including opposition parliamentary leader Lim Kit
Siang.
   Cheah, 40, was arrested for communist subversive activities. The
banned Communist Party of Malaysia has 1,500 guerrillas fighting
from the jungles mainly along the Thailand-Malaysia border.
   Lee, who is a member of Parliament, called on the government to
release Lim and Lim's son, Lim Guan Eng, who have been in jail
without trial under the Internal Security Act since October 1987.
   The two, both members of Parliament, are the only remaining
prisoners of 106 political leaders ordered arrested in 1987 by Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who claimed their actions and speeches
were increasing racial tensions between the Malays and Chinese.
   Lee said about 64 people overall are still being held without
trial under the Internal Security Act. About 550 were detained when
Mahathir became prime minister in 1981. Mahathir called for a review
and released most of them.
   In December, Amnesty International criticized the act, which
empowers authorities to order preventive detention without trial for
activities deemed extremely and imminently dangerous to the state
and the public.
   The London-based human rights group said the act fails to state
clear criteria for identifying such activities, and authorities have
not distinguished between violent activities that threaten national
security and non-violent activities that do not involve such a
threat.
   Amnesty requested a review of the security act. Malaysian laws
are ``seriously inadequate'' to safeguard against arbitrary arrest,
detention without trial, torture or other degrading treatment, it
said.
</TEXT>
