<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Radicals     02-04 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Radicals,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Alliance Vows To Disrupt Hirohito Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several ultraleftist groups have formed an alliance
aimed at disrupting the funeral of Emperor Hirohito, a radical
leader said today.
   Yoshihisa Fujiwara said in an interview that his group ``is in a
common front'' with three other major ultraleftist organizations.
   Speaking with The Associated Press at the heavily fortified
headquarters of his Middle Core Faction, he said the alliance is
planning guerrilla activities to disrupt Hirohito's funeral on Feb.
24.
   He said the alliance includes the Revolutionary Workers'
Association, a group of revolutionaries linked by police to more
than a dozen incidents since Hirohito's health deteriorated in
September. Hirohito died of cancer on Jan. 7.
   Police believe the Middle Core Faction and the Revolutionary
Workers' Association, are Japan's largest ultraleftist groups.
Police say the Marxist-Leninist faction has between 3,000 and 5,000
members, while the Revolutionary Workers' Association has hundreds
of members.
   Fujiwara said the other two groups in the front are the Battle
Flag Faction and the Insurrection Faction.
   Police estimate the Battle Flag Faction membership to be in the
hundreds but are unclear about size of the Insurrection Faction.
Fujiwara refused to estimate the size of any of the groups,
including his own.
   At least half a dozen radical groups have threatened to disrupt
Hirohito's funeral, which will be attended by dignitaries from over
130 nations, including President Bush and Prince Philip of Britain.
More than 30,000 police will be mobilized to ensure their safety.
   Ultraleftists claim the monarchy supports Japanese imperialism,
and they are protesting the state funeral because they say Hirohito
should be treated as a war criminal for his role in World War II.
   Fujiwara, who described himself as a ``ranking member'' of the
Middle Core Faction, refused to say whether Bush is being singled
out as a target but said the American leader's attendance at the
funeral ``is inexcusable.''
   The faction, seen by police as a serious threat to funeral
security, is believed to have the capability of firing missiles more
than 2{ miles.
   After the 1986 Tokyo summit of industrialized nations, it claimed
responsibility for launching missiles that overshot a state guest
house where Western leaders were meeting. ``It is natural to assume
that our technology has improved since then,'' Fujiwara said. He
refused to elaborate.
</TEXT>
