<FIRST>r i PM-Quayle-ElSalvador     02-04 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle-El Salvador,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>El Salvador Must Curb Rights Abuses Or Face Potential Loss Of US
Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, through
a visit by Vice President Dan Quayle, is putting El Salvador on
notice that it must curb human rights abuses or face potential loss
of U.S. aid.
   Quayle also signaled Friday a U.S. willingness to back
postponement of upcoming Salvadoran elections if President Jose
Napoleon Duarte feels he has a consensus mandate to do so.
   Wrapping up the Bush administration's first overseas diplomacy
trip, Quayle made a strong appeal for human rights in El Salvador.
   In a private meeting with top military leaders, he used direct
language reminiscent of a similar mission in 1983 by then Vice
President George Bush, according to officials who attended. Bush had
told the Salvadorans to improve their human rights record or face
loss of further aid.
   ``Quayle was very emphatic in describing the bipartisan
consensus'' in Washington that has led to $3 billion in U.S. aid to
El Salvador during this decade, said one State Department official.
   Quayle explained that the consensus ``is of necessity a very
fragile thing, and that sliding back on the human rights questions
would threaten it.'' The vice president tried ``to tell them the
facts of life in Washington,'' the official said.
   Quayle also met in San Salvador with the two leading candidates
to succeed Duarte as president, and with labor and business leaders,
as well as Archbishop Arturo Rivera y Dama.
   Stopping in El Salvador after two days in Venezuela for that
country's presidential inauguration, Quayle had lunch with Duarte
and several government officials. He offered a toast in which he
praised Duarte as a champion of human rights and repeatedly stressed
U.S. commitment to that cause.
   ``Why I am here today is to reiterate in the strongest terms
possible our commitment to democracy and the advancement of human
rights,'' Quayle told reporters in a news conference later. ``There
are consequences to human rights violations in the future.''
   U.S. commitment and support for El Salvador, he said, ``is
conditioned on advancing democracy and human rights.''
   Human rights abuses, including killing of civilians by right-wing
death squads, were rampant in El Salvador in the early 1980s. The
situation calmed down considerably after 1984, but in the past year
violence by both left and right-wing factions has picked up again.
   Quayle arrived amid tight security at a time when the wartorn
Central American nation is preparing for its March 19 presidential
election.
   The rebels' Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN,
proposed in a peace plan Jan. 23 to postpone the election until
September.
   In the strongest U.S. statement to date on the peace proposal,
Quayle called it ``a step forward.''
   The rebels for the first time ever are offering to participate in
the elections if certain conditions are met, including the
postponement.
   Quayle said ``I'm sure there would be strong support from the
administration'' should Duarte decide he has a national consensus to
agree to the postponement.
</TEXT>
