<FIRST>r i PM-Koreas     02-04 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koreas,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Accuses South Of Warship Provocation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea accused South Korea of committing a
military provocation today by sending four warships into the North's
territorial waters.
   The North's official Korean Central News Agency, monitored in
Tokyo, said the ships sailed deep into its waters off North Korea's
western coast before turning south when a North Korean patrol boat
approached.
   The report did not say whether any shots were fired.
   It was the third reported incident between the two nations in
eight days.
   A North Korean patrol boat seized two South Korean fishing boats
in the Yellow Sea on Jan. 28. On Friday, the North said South Korean
troops fired on a North Korean guard post in the demilitarized zone
separating the countries.
   The North Korean news agency said the alleged warship intrusion
was a ``premeditated and deliberate military provocation aimed at
pushing the situation on the Korean peninsula to an extreme pitch of
strain.''
   South Korea ``must immediately desist from all ... hostile acts
aggravating the situation, which runs counter to the Korean people's
desire for reunification and to the global trend toward universal
detente,'' it said.
   Another agency report today said North Korea would send five
delegates to the truce village of Panmunjom on Wednesday for
negotiations with South Korea over arrangements for talks between
the nations.
   The Koreas have agreed to talks between their prime ministers on
easing military tension and achieving reunification of the divided
peninsula. Such high-level talks have not been held since the
1950-53 Korean War.
   Korea was divided into the communist North and the capitalist
South in 1945, when U.S. and Soviet troops ended Japan's 35-year
colonial rule over Korea. The two Koreas now are involved in their
widest-ranging contacts since the war.
   Earlier today, the South Korean government said an unprecedented
economic agreement reached last week between South Korea's largest
business group and North Korea ``could contribute to efforts to
achieve national unification.''
   The Seoul government said it will propose special legislation to
carry out the agreement between Hyundai and a state-run North Korean
corporation to develop a tourist resort, a shipyard and a railroad
plant in the North.
   Chung Ju-yung, founder and honorary chairman of the Hyundai
group, visited North Korea Jan. 23 to Feb. 1 to discuss the proposed
joint venture.
</TEXT>
