<DOCNO> AP890204-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 0945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan-Vorontsov 1stLd-Writethru a0489 02-04 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Vorontsov, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Afghanistan Pullout to End In Four Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs at the end with Vorontsov discounting rumors of
coup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet troops will complete their
withdrawal from Afghanistan in four days, a senior Soviet official
was quoted as saying today.
   ``As promised, the Soviet Union is evacuating its troops from
Afghanistan. Within four days, there will be no Soviet forces in
Afghanistan,'' Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli Vorontsov was
quoted as saying by Iran's official Tehran Radio.
   Voronstov, who also is the Kremlin's ambassador to Kabul, spoke
after he arrived in Tehran. The broadcast was monitored in Nicosia.
   Under an accord signed last year in Geneva, all Soviet troops are
due to be out of Afghanistan by Feb. 15. Vorontsov's remarks
indicated the Kremlin wanted the pullout completed ahead of the
deadline.
   The radio said Vorontsov would discuss with Iranian officials and
Afghan resistance leaders the future of Afghanistan after the Red
Army's evacuation.
   Vorontsov said, ``At this juncture, it is necessary to discuss
ways of positive reconstruction of that country. It is necessary
that its neighbors exchange views on the future of Afghanistan.''
   ``But of course the future of Afghanistan concerns only the
Afghan people,'' he stressed.
   The Soviet Union intervened in Afghanistan in 1979 to prop up its
Marxist government. At one point the Soviets had about 115,000
troops there.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Nicosia, quoted Vorontsov today as discounting reports of a possible
military coup by hard-line Afghan officers after the Soviet pullout.
   ``There are numerous rumors about Afghanistan, but there is no
such possibility and it is thoroughly baseless,'' he was quoted as
saying.
</TEXT>
