<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru   02-04 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Two; Red Cross Worker Among 24 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with reports of wounded, comments from
the Red Cross, military.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and killed two Palestinian
teen-agers today during clashes with stone-throwers in a refugee
camp in the occupied Gaza Strip, the military said.
   At least 23 Palestinians and a Swiss Red Cross worker were shot
and wounded in riots in Gaza and the occupied West Bank, an Arab
reporter and hospital officials said. The army said only 16 were
wounded.
   The dead boys were identified as 15-year-old Allah Abdullah
Arandez and 16-year-old Maged Jawdat Ihlak. The Arab reporter said
both were shot in the chest during protests in the Khan Younis
refugee camp.
   Since the uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied lands
began 14 months ago, 373 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been
killed.
   A military official confirmed today's deaths, but said Arandez
was 24 and not 15 as reported by the hospital.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
troops were forced to fire after a group of women and masked youths
surrounded their lookout point in the refugee camp and threw rocks.
The incident was under investigation, the official said.
   Arandez's family took his body from the camp hospital and quickly
arranged a funeral, which was followed by a protest march through
the camp.
   Arandez was the second member of his family to be killed in the
uprising, Arab reporters said. His brother, 26-year-old Sabri
Abdullah, was shot and killed in November, they said.
   In the clashes with troops that followed the funeral, 20
Palestinians were shot and wounded, including Ihlak, who died in the
operating room, said refugee camp hospital officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The wounded also included four teen-age girls and a 25-year-old
man who was in critical condition, the officials said.
   Alexander Antonin, a Swiss Red Cross worker, was shot in the leg
after arriving at the Khan Younis camp to help arrange the
evacuation of wounded, said Frederick Maurice, head of the
International Committee of the Red Cross in Israel and the occupied
areas.
   Antonin had followed ambulances into the camp and was negotiating
with troops about evacuations when more riots broke out, Maurice
said.
   ``He was in between the soldiers and the protesters. ... There
was also tear gas, and it was very difficult to see what was going
on. There was stone throwing on one side of the street and shooting
on the other,'' Maurice said. ``It was a bit of a mess.'' He said
the Red Cross has not decided whether to file a complaint with the
Israeli army.
   ``It's possible an accident happened,'' he said.
   The army imposed a curfew on the camp and ordered all 35,000
residents to remain at home, an Arab reporter said.
   In other clashes, four Palestinians were wounded in the Dir El
Balah and Rafah refugee camps in the Gaza Strip and in the occupied
West Bank town of Kalkilya, hospital officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
