<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MissingRobe     02-04 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Missing Robe,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thief Swipes Judge's Robe From Courthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are circulating a sketch of a thief
who swiped a judge's custom robe from the county courthouse during a
recess.
   ``At first, I thought someone was playing a prank on me,'' said
Montgomery County Superior Court Judge Thomas W. Ross.
``Unfortunately, the robe was given to me as a Christmas present by
my wife. My name was monogrammed in the back.''
   Sheriff's deputies say they believe the would-be jurist was a man
who asked a clerk for directions to Ross' courtroom during the
recess.
   The $150 black robe was taken Jan. 25 as Ross lunched with the
sheriff, district attorney and other court personnel. He last saw it
hanging in a lounge between the courtroom and the judge's chambers.
   Two other judges' robes hanging nearby were not taken.
   ``It was one of the better-looking robes,'' said sheriff's Capt.
Richard Russell.
   The judge, who now wears a spare robe, takes the robe-napping in
stride.
   ``It could have been worse,'' he said. ``Someone could have put a
hole through it while I was wearing it.''
