<DOCNO> AP890204-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GesellProfile     02-04 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gesell Profile,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Gesell's Dilemma Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Trial Judge Called Stern, Smart, Fair, Not Lacking In Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well before Oliver L. North's trial got under
way in Courtroom 6, Judge Gerhard A. Gesell asked how long it would
last, telling lawyers ``far more important matters'' awaited his
attention.
   Sparring from the bench with defense lawyers and prosecutors
alike, the energetic 78-year-old federal district judge obviously
relishes the limelight and legal challenges posed by the first
criminal trial in the Iran-Contra affair.
   But despite the national attention given the case, Gesell took
pains at the Jan. 9 hearing to remind the lawyers that he will treat
it like just another criminal matter on his crowded docket.
   ``It has become increasingly urgent for me to know how long this
case is going to take,'' Gesell said at the hearing. ``There are a
substantial number of litigants with _ I think _ far more important
matters pending who want to be heard.
   ``I've got all kinds of problems in terms of the work of the
court as an institution,'' said Gesell, who unlike most judges his
age has refused to take a reduced caseload by going on ``senior
status.''
   Told the trial could last four or five months, Gesell replied,
``It will be a wonderful summer.''
   Highly regarded for his intellect and ability to conduct a
difficult trial, Gesell is known among Washington lawyers as being
impatient with slipshod pleadings and arguments.
   ``You better be prepared, but he gives you a fair hearing on
everything,'' said attorney James Jordan, a former bar association
president who has tried a number of civil cases before Gesell.
   Others note a touch of intellectual arrogance in Gesell, the son
of a noted Yale University child psychologist.
   ``Sometimes wrong, never in doubt,'' said one attorney, echoing _
on condition of anonymity _ a sentiment expressed by other
colleagues in the local bar. ``He does a lot of thinking out loud, a
sign of self-confidence of which he is not lacking.''
   Gesell's habit of expressing his thoughts from the bench has sent
many a reporter scurrying to the telephone with excited accounts
about the judge's latest doubts about the future of the Iran-Contra
case.
   At the outset of jury selection, Gesell said the difficulty
finding prospective jurors who had no knowledge of North's immunized
congressional testimony raised questions about ``the triability of
the case.''
   Yet after five days, the judge managed to find 32 prospective
jurors for a planned pool of 50, from which the panel will be
selected.
   Gesell can also be hot tempered as he was when he threatened an
ABC News reporter with a contempt-of-court citation for airing an
account of jury selection that he said ``appears to be a deliberate
effort'' to disrupt the process.
   The judge's storm of vituperation quickly passed and there has
been no further mention of contempt proceedings against the
television reporter, Tim O'Brien.
   Gesell's experience with big cases and troubling issues
throughout his 20-year career on the bench no doubt figured in the
decision by Aubrey E. Robinson Jr., the chief judge of U.S. District
Court here, to assign the Iran-Contra cases to him.
   Throughout the pre-trial maneuverings several judges expressed
the view that if any jurist could bring the difficult case to trial
it would be Gesell.
   ``He is just very much in control,'' said William Jeffress, a
criminal defense lawyer who clerked for Gesell in the early 1970s.
``I would certainly say he has a dominating personality. He is and
remains in control of what goes on in his court.''
   Gesell has had his share of other famous cases, notably the
Watergate plumbers case in 1974, which involved the conspiracy to
break into the office of a Los Angeles psychiatrist to get the
patient records of Daniel Ellsberg, who leaked the Pentagon Papers
to The New York Times.
   Gesell refused in 1971 to enjoin The Washington Post from
publishing its version of the secret Pentagon study of the Vietnam
War.
   He was the only federal judge who refused to grant the Justice
Department's requests for injunctions to delay newpaper publication
of the Pentagon Papers _ a position vindicated by a unanimous
Supreme Court decision in the case.
   A year earlier, Gesell had enjoined the Government Printing
Office from publishing a House Internal Security Committee report
listing 65 ``radical revolutionary'' campus speakers. The judge
found it had served no ``legislative purpose and was issued solely
for exposure for intimidation.''
   After attending Yale as an undergraduate and law student, Gesell
came to Washington during the New Deal and went to work at the
Securities and Exchange Commission for William O. Douglas, who later
became a Supreme Court justice.
   At the SEC, Gesell successfully investigated a major Wall Street
investment scandal _ an episode Douglas cites in his memoirs. Later,
Gesell became a partner for the celebrated Washington law firm of
Covington and Burling, making his mark as an anti-trust lawyer.
   With his rosy cheeks, the white-haired jurist was once aptly
described by The New York Times as resembling a clean-shaven Santa
Claus. Known among friends as a jovial raconteur, Gesell usually
spends the month of August at his summer home on an island off the
cost of Maine.
   On most weekends, he and his wife, Peggy, go to their dairy farm
near Leesburg, Va., where he produces his own brand of honey that is
sold in local stores and vegetable stands.
   Jeffress said Gesell is not just a ``gentleman farmer who goes
out and gets waited on, but a farmer who gets his feet dirty.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890204-0079 </DOCNO>
