<DOCNO> AP890204-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AIDS-World     02-04 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-World,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly 140,000 AIDS Cases Reported Worldwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Health Organization says 7,000 new AIDS
cases were reported last month, raising the worldwide total to
nearly 140,000.
   Most of the increase was due to updated reports on acquired
immune deficiency syndrome from the Americas and Europe, WHO said
Friday in its monthly update on the spread of the deadly disease.
   The United States reported more than half of the new cases,
nearly 4,000.
   WHO estimated the real number of adult cases was between 350,000
and 400,000 by the end of last year, with sub-Saharan Africa thought
to account for more than half the victims. The U.N. agency noted
that the accuracy of reports on AIDS patients varies widely between
countries and continents.
   WHO said 139,886 cases were reported from 144 countries by Jan.
31, a rise of 6,910 over a month earlier. Thirty-three countries
said they had no cases.
   New Caledonia, the French Pacific territory, reported its first
victims: two as of Aug. 1.
   The United States, which has recorded 60 percent of all AIDS
cases, reported 3,965 new cases last month.
   France, with the highest total and case rate in Europe, reported
an increase of 781 to 5,655 cases.
   Italy reported 452 new victims, bringing its total to 3,008.
   Spain's figure rose to 2,165 with the report of 315 new cases.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by
drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
