<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TowerConfirmation     02-04 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower Confirmation,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>New, Private Allegations Prompt Committee Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower's reputation and the intent of the
Senate Armed Services Committee to conduct a thorough investigation
collided head-on this week as the expected confirmation of the
defense secretary-designate hit a snag.
   New allegations surfaced Thursday of a drinking problem and
womanizing, prompting the committee to postpone a planned vote on
Tower's nomination until the FBI could complete a new inquiry.
   Despite the new twist to the well-circulated but unsubstantiated
rumors, senators said they expect the Senate panel to approve the
Tower nomination and forward their recommendation to the full Senate.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the panel,
said he expected the FBI report to reach the panel on Monday, ``and
... we can proceed to vote Tuesday or Wednesday.''
   Tower was dogged by allegations of drinking and womanizing before
his nomination. In divorce papers filed two years ago by his second
wife, Lilla Burt Cummings, Tower was accused of ``marital
misconduct.''
   When President Bush announced Tower's appointment, he said an FBI
background check found nothing that would prevent Tower from serving
as defense secretary. Bush dismissed ``a lot of rumors that proved
to be groundless.''
   The ranking members of the committee, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and
Warner, read the FBI report, and any questions about Tower's
personal life were reserved for executive sessions with committee
members.
   But when conservative lobbyist Paul Weyrich testified Tuesday at
the committee's open hearing that ``on a number of occasions'' he
had seen Tower inebriated and in the company of women other than his
wife, the former senator's lifestyle was pushed to the forefront.
   One day later, according to congressional sources, the committee
and the White House received new allegations regarding Tower, and
the vote was postponed.
   Complicating matters is the committee's concerns about an
appearance of conflict of interest.
   After his 24-year tenure in the Senate, including a stint as
chairman of the Armed Services Committee, Tower worked as a defense
consultant for such industry giants as Rockwell and Martin-Marietta.
In his testimony, Tower said he received more than $1 million in
consulting fees over a 2{-year period.
   Although Tower said he had severed all ties with the companies,
and promised to recuse himself from any decision on an Air Force
electronics system that he had lobbied for, members of the committee
still voiced concern over conflict of interest.
   ``But what is the difference, in terms of the appearance, as to
whether or not you lobbied Congress for a program or whether or not
you advanced that program through other means?'' Sen. Carl Levin,
D-Mich., asked Tower on Wednesday. ``Isn't the same connection to
that program in existence?''
   ``Senator, that's a judgment call on my part, and that's the only
one in which I might have had some profile,'' Tower responded. ``I
would emphasize I am not legally required to do this, but I have an
abundance of caution, and that's a judgment call that I'm making
myself.''
   The committee also is conscious of its experience with Melvyn
Paisley, a key figure in the Pentagon procurement investigation.
Paisley was nominated in 1981 as assistant secretary of Navy and
later confirmed.
   Tower, committee chairman at the time, said the White House
refused the panel's request to see the FBI report on Paisley. Nunn
and Warner said if they had known of the allegations against Paisley
they would have withheld approval until the charges had been checked.
   The ranking members of the 1989 committee would like to avoid a
similar incident.
   ``It's not over till it's over,'' Nunn said Thursday. ``The
investigation is not over until all serious allegations have been
checked, and that's the process we always follow.''
</TEXT>
