<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     02-04 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Demonstrate Against Soviet Policy in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of supporters of a Moslem party
demonstrated Saturday near the Soviet Embassy to protest what they
called the Red Army's ``continued atrocities in Afghanistan.''
   More than 500 members of the Bangladesh Moslem Movement
participated in the protest.
   Witnesses said two truckloads of policemen followed the
protestors as they marched toward the Soviet Embassy. The
demonstrators were stopped a few hundred yards from the embassy, but
a six-member delegation was allowed to enter the mission to submit a
memorandum, according to the witnesses.
   Party chief Maulana Azizur Rahman said the Soviets were killing
Afghan Moslems ``with a sense of vengeance.''
   ``They have adopted a scorched-earth policy to kill Moslem
brethren and destroy Afghanistan,'' he told a meeting of the
demonstrators. ``The peace-loving people of the world will not
tolerate this.''
   ``It is painful to believe that the Soviets continue their
barbarism in Afghanistan even when they are withdrawing for the
establishment of peace in the region,'' said Maulana Shamsur Rahman,
another party leader.
   The Soviets have been accused of heavily bombing Afghan villages
along the Salang Highway, the route taken by withdrawing Soviet
soldiers, to reduce attacks by Moslem guerrillas stationed nearby.
   Soviet troops moved into Afghanistan in 1979 to support the
Marxist government in a civil war against Moslem rebels.
   Under a U.N.-sponsored accord last year, the Soviet troops are
scheduled to withdraw from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
