<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissident     02-04 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissident,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Dissident Brings Pro-Democracy Message to Establishment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's leading dissident, Fang Lizhi, took his
message straight to the establishment Saturday by telling a party
attended by hundreds of actors, scientists, and businessmen they
should work for human rights.
   ``Some people think China doesn't need democracy, but I think
human rights is basic,'' Fang said in a strong voice. Until his
speech, the tea party had been non-political with some guests
volunteering songs and stories.
   ``For (human rights) to be realized, first of all famous people
must take a stand,'' he told the audience, which included many local
leaders in the arts, science and trade.
   Fang and several other leading intellectuals were expelled from
the Communist Party in 1987 after nationwide student demonstrations
for democracy.
   More recently, authorities punished Fang for his outspokenness by
revoking his permission to spend six months this year at the
Colorado Joint Institute for Laboratory Astrophysics.
   Fang, who is also known for his work as an astrophysicist, has
made many pro-democracy speech to groups of sympathizers,
particularly students.
   However, Saturday was the first time he took his message of
democracy and human rights to an establishment audience.
   The party at a local hotel was organized by the Chinese Cultural
Academy and Academy of Sciences' Entrepreneurial Association to
celebrate the upcoming Lunar New Year. Both groups are state-run.
   ``Some people came up to me afterward and said they agreed with
what I said,'' Fang said after his speech, which ended to tepid
applause. But he acknowledged that not everyone in the audience was
happy.
   ``I will speak out more in the future to such groups,'' Fang
said. ``I think there will be more and more discussions among
intellectuals ... because the government right now is very weak due
to economic problems. Even inside the party, they can't agree on
things.''
   China is trying to control inflation of more than 20 percent,
shortages of energy and raw materials, and growing corruption.
</TEXT>
