<DOCNO> AP890204-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Gesell'sDilemma Bjt   02-04 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gesell's Dilemma, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Same Judge, Same Legal Dilemmas in North Trial and Watergate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The intense publicity, the fight over secret
documents, the legal dilemmas posed at the trial of Oliver North
rouse memories of a celebrated Watergate trial at which U.S.
District Judge Gerhard Gesell also presided.
   As he began jury selection last week in the trial of the former
White House aide, the white-haired judge with the no-nonsense manner
followed procedures he used more than 14 years ago for the so-called
Plumbers trial.
   A defendant in that case was an aide from an earlier White House
_ John Ehrlichman, former chief domestic adviser to Richard M. Nixon.
   Courtroom No. 6 on the second floor of the U.S. District
Courthouse was the scene of that trial, as it is the North trial.
   There are other similarities.
   Like North, Ehrlichman was a prodigious note-taker who contended
his files were essential to his defense.
   Like North, Ehrlichman had starred on television as a featured
witness at hearings watched by millions of Americans.
   Like North, Ehrlichman's role in a White House scandal was the
subject of front-page stories that intrigued a nation for months
before his case came to trial.
   Despite the torrent of publicity, it took Gesell just two days to
seat a jury for the Plumbers trial _ named for the White House unit
established to plug leaks of classified information. Only three
potential jurors were dismissed because they said they doubted they
could render an impartial verdict.
   But the North trial presents Gesell with a problem he didn't face
14 years ago. Ehrlichman didn't have immunity when he testified
before the Senate Watergate committee. North did have a guarantee
his testimony before the congressional Iran-Contra committee
couldn't be used against him.
   Dozens of prospective jurors have been dismissed from the North
trial because they said they heard North testify to Congress that he
committed crimes.
   The search for an untainted jury in the North trial ``is
exacerbated by the immunity,'' said Richard Ben-Veniste, one of the
Watergate prosecutors.
   ``This case has more problems than any I've ever seen,'' said
Ben-Veniste, who played a leading role in the trial of former Nixon
administration officials convicted on charges stemming from the
break-in at Democratic Party headquarters in the Watergate office
building.
   What has struck some observers of the North trial is the search
for people who had no curiosity about the Iran-Contra scandal when
it was unfolding in televised hearings.
   ``Whether they will differ from normal, average jurors remains to
be seen,'' said Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., a former state supreme
court judge who served on the Iran-Contra committee. ``If a man
never saw anything of it, what type of individual is he?''
   ``I wouldn't want people who lived in Washington, the seat of
government, on that jury who were so uninformed,'' said Bill
Moffitt, a criminal defense attorney.
   The magnitude of Gesell's problem was illustrated by the case of
a prospective juror disqualified because she worked at a Sears
Roebuck store where dozens of TV sets were turned on when North
testified in July 1987.
   The woman has not watched the testimony, but her exposure to it
was such that the judge decided to remove her from the panel of
potential jurors.
   Documents are another common issue.
   In both cases, Gesell made extraordinary appeals to the
president, but the tone of each was quite different.
   In the North case, Gesell urged President Reagan to decide
whether massive amounts of classified information North contended
was vital to his defense could be released.
   ``The court has a very limited role,'' said Gesell, adding that
the Constitution provides that it is up to the president ``not North
or any witness, to protect the prerogatives of the president's
office if he deems them unduly threatened.''
   North had sought some 40,000 pages of documents.
   When the president refused to release material _ saying ``these
are things that are national security secrets'' _ conspiracy charges
against North were dropped.
   Gesell never implied he thought the White House was withholding
material simply to block prosecution of the man Reagan had once
referred to as ``a national hero.''
   The judge's attitude was very different when he came into
conflict with the Nixon White House over Ehrlichman's request to
have access to his files.
   When the White House said that only the defendant, not his
lawyer, would be allowed into the room where the files were kept,
Gesell responded scathingly.
   ``I don't see how I can agree to a procedure that is so totally
offensive,'' he said.
   ``It is offensive, sir, it borders on obstruction,'' he told
James St. Clair, the lawyer representing Nixon at various
proceedings then underway to examine the president's role in
Watergate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
