<DOCNO> AP890204-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PlantClosings-Steel     02-04 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Closings-Steel,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Employees Get Closing Notice; But Jobs Still Leaving</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fritz Wagner once lost a job with less than
a week's notice, so he appreciated getting two months' warning of
the closing of Lehigh Structural Steel Co.'s fabricating plant.
   That notice under a new federal law is only so much help, though.
   ``You're out of a job no matter how you look at it,'' Wagner, 23,
said Friday in a drizzle at the lunch truck outside the 70-year-old
factory.
   Lehigh Structural Steel President R. Leslie Mullen, citing
inability to compete in the Northeast with Canadian companies,
announced Jan. 24 that the company would shut down most of its
Allentown operations permanently by March 24, putting about 185 of
225 employees out of work.
   A new law that took effect Saturday requires companies with 100
or more full-time employees to give 60 days' notice of plant
closings or major layoffs. Under some interpretations of the law,
Lehigh had to give notice even before the Feb. 4 effective date, and
the company provided it.
   ``It's not like you can come in one day and the doors are
locked,'' Wagner said. The notice, he said, means ``now we've got a
chance'' to look for other jobs.
   A union official said that notice may not be a big help for many
of his members, but said company officials have been straightforward.
   ``They're abiding by the plant-closing law. They've been really
cooperative,'' secretary-treasurer John Kontier of Local 548 of the
International Association of Bridge, Structural and Ornamental
Ironworkers union.
   The law doesn't require that each employee receives 60 days'
notice, because some employees may be laid off before a plant closes
entirely.
   ``They just said the plant's shutting down. Then I got a
three-day layoff notice,'' said John Shelby, a punch operator at the
plant for five years who was one of seven or eight workers laid off
Friday. He said he thought he should have received more notice.
   Even with 60 days' notice, job counseling under way and
retraining to start soon, Kontier said, the law may not get his
members quickly back to work. He said they will first search in vain
for jobs that pay near the steel plant's average $10 to $11 an hour,
plus benefits including health insurance.
   He wants to see more government efforts to keep companies in
business, particularly in making sure foreign companies don't get an
unfair advantage in markets.
   But those would be too late for this company. Gradual layoffs
began in January and one fabricating shop closed a week ago, with
another scheduled to close this week, said plant superintendent Ken
Weiss, who at 59 will be looking for a job himself.
   By the target closing date of the entire plant in April, the last
shop will have finished the remaining steelwork for a 41-story
building in New York. Weiss said about 30 employees will be needed
for the last stage.
   The shutdown plans surprised Wagner, who began work at the plant
last May. He liked the idea of the new law, but little did he know
as politicians fussed over its passage last year that it would
affect him.
   ``I had no feeling at all. When I started in May, I thought my
job was set,'' said Wagner, who bought a house last September and
was married in October. ``I thought I could retire here.''
   ``My whole family worked here,'' he said. ``My grandfather was
here when they opened the plant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
