<DOCNO> AP890204-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-B-1Study     02-04 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-1 Study,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Problems With New Bomber Persist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major problems still plaguing the B-1B bomber
may reduce its expected range and payload capability, says a report
issued by Congress' investigative arm.
   The General Accounting Office concluded in its report that
although the Air Force has made progress in correcting certain
deficiencies in the Rockwell-built bomber, problems in the bomber's
performance persist.
   ``Several areas critical to B-1B's mission performance have not
yet been demonstrated,'' the report said.
   The review also said the cost of the Air Force plane could be up
to $400 million each if the service goes ahead with all the planned
improvements.
   Those problems mean the B-1B may not have the range it was
designed to have or be able to carry all the bombs and missiles
planned for it, the report said.
   The bomber is designed to carry conventional and nuclear gravity
bombs, cruise missiles and short-range attack missiles.
   Specifically, the report said the Air Force has not made progress
in resolving problems with the B-1B's defensive avionics. ``In
short, it is now known that the defensive avionics cannot meet
specifications without a major redesign,'' the report said.
   The defensive avionics, or electronic countermeasures system, was
designed to improve the bomber's probability of penetrating the
Soviet Union by allowing the aircraft's crew to ``avoid, degrade and
deceive the Soviet air defenses,'' the report said.
   The problems involve the system's radar warning receiver and
processor function.
   The report also said that data for the bomber indicate that
reported fuel leaks have for the most part remained the same over
the last year. Elimination of the fuel leaks is probably not
possible, according to the report, which noted that the fuel cells
are part of the airframe and seals and joints are subjected to
flight stress.
   The B-1, killed by then-President Carter in 1977, was resurrected
four years later by former President Reagan, who said 100 of the
swing-wing planes were needed to update the nation's aging force of
nuclear-armed bombers.
   Reagan ordered 100 of the planes, at a cost of $20.5 billion.
Three have crashed, leaving the service with 97 B-1Bs. The Air Force
has already received all the B-1s it intends to buy and is now
proceeding with plans to buy the radar-evading B-2 stealth bomber.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
