<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ObsceneTicket     02-04 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Obscene Ticket,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sues City After Arrest For Writing Obscenity On Parking Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Morgenstern paid his traffic fine
and gave a little something extra _ an obscene note complaining
about the parking ticket.
   Now he is suing the city for $1.8 million, saying his free speech
rights were violated when he was arrested for scrawling the
obscenity on the traffic ticket.
   ``There were no (expletive) signs posted anywhere,'' Morgenstern
had written on the $12 ticket in June 1987.
   Morgenstern filed a lawsuit Friday in U.S. District Court seeking
$1 million in punitive damages and $800,000 in compensatory damages
from Rochester and Lester Roden, city parking violations enforcement
supervisor. Roden had Morgenstern arrested for second-degree
harassment a few weeks after he paid the parking ticket.
   The harassment charge was dismissed Aug. 10, 1988, by City Court
Judge William H. Bristol, who wrote: ``We who work in government ...
must expect that a certain disdain for government will be expressed
to us by citizens. After all, we are employed by these citizens.
They are our sovereigns.''
</TEXT>
