<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Quakes     02-04 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quakes,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tadzhikistan Hit by More Tremors; Problems in Armenia Reconstruction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two tremors on Saturday rocked the area of
Tadzhikistan where an earthquake and mudslide killed 274 people last
month, Tass reported. No damage or injuries were reported.
   Also Saturday, the official news agency said a high-level
commission was unhappy with reconstruction of the area of Armenia
devastated by a Dec. 7 quake that killed an estimated 25,000 people.
   Tass said two tremors measuring 4 on the 12-point Soviet scale
jolted the area of Gissar in Tadzhikistan, 1,800 miles southeast of
Moscow in Soviet Central Asia. On Friday, tremors of 4 and 2-3
points were reported, it said.
   A tremor of 4 points can shake objects such as dishes and windows
and cause doors and walls to creak.
   A 40-second earthquake struck Tadzhikistan on Jan. 23, loosening
layers of mud that tumbled through mountain villages 20 miles
southwest of the republic's capital, Dushanbe.
   In the Armenian capital, Yerevan, a commission of the country's
ruling Politburo met Saturday and lashed out at construction
officials for dragging their feet in rebuilding the city of Spitak,
Tass reported. The commission said the delays could seriously set
back rebuilding plans.
   Spitak was one of the hardest hit areas by the December
earthquake, and the town is to be rebuilt several miles away from
its current location. The current location is right at the
convergence of three earthquake faults.
   The Kremlin has promised to rebuild northwestern Armenia in two
years.
   The panel said that to speed reconstruction, it was ordering
increases in local production of building materials such as sand,
stone and gravel.
   Tass said the sanitary and health conditions in the disaster area
remained poor. It said the danger of epidemics will increase as
spring approaches and the weather warms up.
</TEXT>
