<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Amnesty     02-04 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Amnesty,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Government Frees Nine Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola freed nine anti-government
guerrillas from jail in an amnesty that began Saturday, a Portuguese
news agency said.
   The amnesty is aimed at U.S.-backed rebels from the National
Union for Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA. It affects
Angolans living both inside Angola and abroad.
   However, the rebels have rejected the amnesty and pledged to keep
up their 13-year war against their country's leftist government.
   The Portuguese news agency Lusa said the rebels were released
from a jail in the Angolan capital, Luanda.
   It did not say how long they were imprisoned or what the charges
were.
   The rebels have also rejected U.S.-brokered peace accords signed
in December by Angola, South Africa and Cuba.
   Under the pacts, South Africa pledged to cut off aid to the
Angolan rebels and grant independence to neighboring Namibia. In
return, about 50,000 pro-government Cuban troops in Angola have
begun a phased withdrawal.
   The United States has promised to support UNITA until the Soviet
Union ends aid to the Angolan government.
</TEXT>
