<FIRST>u w AM-Quayle Bjt   02-04 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, Bjt,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Emerges From First Foreign Trip Unbloodied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle is back home from his
first foray abroad for the Bush administration, apparently with
neither great gaffes nor startling accomplishments to show for his
largely symbolic mission to Latin America.
   Quayle, meeting in Venezuela with world leaders at a presidential
inauguration, signaled Bush administration sensitivity to Latin
America and then went to El Salvador where he delivered a stern
human rights message to the U.S.-backed government.
   The Latins had waited with great curiosity to size up the new
vice president while his own countrymen watched to see how he would
handle his first major assignment from President Bush.
   Foreign service officials nervously hoped he would not live down
to campaign criticisms that he was not up to the job of vice
president.
   By many accounts from both U.S. and foreign officials, the
diplomatic greenhorn acquitted himself well on the international
stage, even displaying a certain verve for his mission.
   In Venezuela, where his job was mostly to spread goodwill,
Quayle's affable, political style was a hit with Latin leaders who
place great store in ``personalismo,'' one member of the U.S.
delegation said.
   ``I was skeptical but I'm impressed,'' said Michael Skol, a State
Department Latin America specialist who traveled with Quayle. After
one day of meetings, Skol said, ``He's making the right political
moves, the right body language. ... He's not saying too much when he
shouldn't say too much.''
   In El Salvador, a harder line was called for as Quayle went
before some 20 military officers who lead the nation's 56,000-member
armed forces. He delivered what was described by U.S. officials as
an emphatic admonition on the need for progress in curbing human
rights abuses.
   Quayle took that same message to the country's political and
business leaders, leaving a clear message that future U.S. aid will
be linked to the country's success on human rights.
   In Caracas, Quayle was a less dominant figure in the company of
some 20 heads of state and countless seasoned diplomats at the
inauguration of President Carlos Andres Perez.
   Aside from Perez, the center stage figure was the
larger-than-life Fidel Castro of Cuba. He was ubiquitous on
television screens and he sat not far from Quayle at the
inauguration. The two did not speak to each other.
   Quayle's hectic schedule during two days in Caracas included
bilateral meetings with 10 heads of state, and less formal meetings
with about the same number.
   While the former senator's diplomatic inexperience did not go
unnoticed, that was not necessarily a negative factor in these
get-acquainted sessions, according to those familiar with them.
   ``The vice president left behind some extremely positive
feelings. He was well informed but at the same time he elicited the
opinions of the leaders he met with in a very sincere way,'' said
Otto Reich, the U.S. ambassador to Venezuela.
   `He's getting experience here,'' said Francisco Aguilar Urbina, a
Harvard-educated adviser to Costa Rica President Oscar Arias.
   He said the Latins had been unsure what to expect, having heard
mostly negative news reports about Quayle.
   Urbina said Quayle, while not a particularly imposing figure, was
projecting a positive image.
   ``They liked the fact that he went out of his way, broke with
protocol and just did things with regular people,'' said a member of
the U.S. delegation.
   Quayle on two occasions mingled with ordinary Brazilians, once
stopping his motorcade on the way from the airport to buy fruit at a
local market.
   He also visited a popular plaza where he worked a crowd campaign
style.
   A few hundred people quickly gathered and Quayle stepped up to a
statue of regional hero Simon Bolivar and pleased the crowd by
declaring Bolivar a hero of democracy in the United States as well.
   In his energetic, upbeat style, Quayle made friendly small talk
to get his bilateral meetings with heads of state underway.
   As photographers recorded the start of their meeting, he talked
with Costa Rica's Arias about mutual acquaintances in the U.S.
Senate. With Peru's President Alan Garcia he joked about his
upcoming 42nd birthday.
   Quayle was seen as ``sensible'' by President Jose Sarney of
Brazil, said Sarney's spokesman, Carlos Henrique de Almeida. He
indicated the Brazilians also see Quayle as a new guy on the job who
has a lot to learn.
   ``They were testing each other. Sarney was very clear and open,''
without the customary diplomatic verbiage, and Quayle was the same
way, de Almeida said.
   Guatemala's President Vinicio Cerezo subtly noted Quayle's
newcomer status, saying this was ``a really good opportunity for you
to come here and meet many leaders from Latin countries ... for you
especially.''
</TEXT>
