<FIRST>r a AM-AlteredResume     02-04 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Altered Resume,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former City Manager Pleads No Contest to Theft Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of falsifying his resume to
gain government and police jobs in several states pleaded no contest
to a theft charge and agreed to find another line of work.
   Carl Keyser Jr., 34, was fired from the city administrator's job
in the tiny southeastern Alaska village of Kake in December, one day
after he was arrested on a Kentucky fugitive warrant.
   He was charged in Kake with felony first-degree theft for using a
bogus resume to get hired and obtain $28,000 worth of salary,
benefits and expenses. He entered his no-contest plea Friday, but it
was not immediately approved by a judge. During a hearing held via
telephone, Superior Court Judge Thomas Schultz in Ketchikan took the
agreement under advisement and said he would wait for a probation
report on Keyser before deciding whether to accept it.
   Keyser, who had been in jail in nearby Petersburg since his
arrest, remains wanted in Pikeville, Ky., on another theft charge
stemming from his six-day stint as Pikeville's city manager last
August.
   In a plea agreement to settle the Kake charge, Keyser agreed to a
jail term of up to 90 days with credit for time already served,
which is about half of that. The agreement requires Keyser to pay
restitution for the money he received during the 2{ months he was on
the job, and would place Keyser on probation for seven years.
   The maximum penalties for first-degree theft are 10 years in
prison and a $100,000 fine.
   Keyser also agreed not to accept any type of government
employment, to sign a letter of apology to the town, and to remain
in Petersburg while awaiting sentencing.
   Schultz reduced bail on both theft charges to $2,500 each and
Keyser posted bail after Friday's hearing.
   Residents in Kake, a timber and fishing town about 75 miles south
of Juneau on Kupreanof Island, became suspicious of Keyser shortly
after he took the $44,000-a-year job. They accused him of
overspending and criticized him for refusing to release his resume
for public inspection.
   A police records check in December revealed the outstanding
Kentucky warrant.
   Interviews with prosecutors and city officials in several states
revealed that at least 19 of Keyser's jobs since 1980 have been with
city or county governments. Documents and the interviews also showed
Keyser used false information while obtaining at least 11 jobs.
   Kake officials have said they hired him because of an impressive
resume and people who gave glowing references. But they now believe
the resume and the references who were contacted by telephone were
fraudulent.
   Assistant District Attorney Steven West in Ketchikan said Friday
that Pikeville officials probably would dismiss their charge against
Keyser.
   Last month, Pikeville city commissioners asked the prosecutor
there to drop the charge, but the prosecutor said at the time that
he wanted to continue to press the case.
   In Pikeville, Keyser is accused of theft by deception for failure
to reimburse the city for $697 in travel expenses.
   Keyser declined to comment on the Kake case after the hearing. He
said he planned to do community and church volunteer work while
awaiting sentencing.
   In an interview in December, he maintained his innocence and said
the charges were the result of a conspiracy in Pikeville. Keyser
accused the news media and officials of seeking to make an example
of him.
</TEXT>
