<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan     02-04 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Says Unpaid Leave Will Avoid Appearance of Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabinet nominee Louis Sullivan said Saturday he
would take an unpaid leave of absence from his medical school while
serving as health and human services secretary to avoid any
appearance of a conflict of interest.
   Sullivan, president of the Morehouse School of Medicine in
Atlanta, had wanted to maintain his ties to the school with a paid
leave, but he withdrew the request after the White House raised
questions about the arrangement.
   ``I intend to preclude even the remotest possibility of any
appearance that my actions as secretary might be influenced due to
any outside income,'' Sullivan said in a statement released by the
White House.
   Sullivan said he has asked the medical school's executive
committee to grant him an unpaid leave of absence while he serves in
the Bush administration.
   White House spokesman B. Jay Cooper said an unpaid leave would
mean the school ``would suspend any salary payments while he served
as secretary of HHS.''
   Sullivan earns about $170,000 a year from Morehouse, it was
learned.
   The arrangement is designed to avoid any conflict of interest
that could arise because Morehouse gets federal funds for its
programs. In fiscal 1988, the school received $5.8 million from HHS.
   Federal ethics officials indicated last week that Sullivan would
be able to receive payments from the school while serving at HHS.
Don Campbell, deputy director of the Office of Government Ethics,
said ethics officials had met with Sullivan and his lawyers and
``all the problems have been worked out.''
   A government source familiar with Sullivan's situation said the
nominee had a specific written contract entitling him to certain
payments for a leave of absence, based on days of service.
   Morehouse, like many academic institutions, gives its faculty
paid sabbatical leaves based on years of service. Sullivan was
allowed a paid sabbatical after 13 years of uninterupted service,
the White House said.
   The New York Times, in Saturday's editions, quoted a friend of
Sullivan's as saying the nominee had accrued about $300,000 worth of
sabbatical leave.
   But Sullivan said in his statement, ``President Bush has called
on all of those in his Cabinet ... to set the very highest ethical
standards, and to avoid even the appearance of potential conflicts
of interest. I agree emphatically with the president.''
   Sullivan's decision resolves one of the issues that has held up
his confirmation hearings in the Senate.
   The Senate Finance Committee last week postponed Sullivan's
confirmation hearings indefinitely at the request of the White House.
   The panel is awaiting completion of an FBI background check that
is focusing in part on Sullivan's ties to Reginald Eaves, a
suspended Fulton County, Ga., commissioner who has been convicted of
extortion.
   In a matter unrelated to the extortion case, Eaves was paid more
than $34,000 over four years as a lecturer at Morehouse while using
his seat on the commission to promote matters beneficial to the
school. He reportedly gave two lectures at Morehouse over the four
years.
   The Eaves controversy, however, does not appear to threaten
Sullivan's confirmation, according to lawmakers.
</TEXT>
