<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Bomb     02-04 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bomb,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Dispose Of Big World War II Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts on Saturday safely disposed of a
2,000-pound German bomb that had been buried since the World War II
blitz in the city's East End.
   Several hundred people were evacuated from their homes Friday
night after construction workers unearthed the huge bomb at a
building site.
   Army bomb disposal officers were called to the scene and worked
through the night, police at Scotland Yard headquarters said.
   Because the bomb was considered too dangerous to try to transport
out of the area, the army experts steamed explosives out of the
shell and conducted a controlled explosion of the detonator, police
and the Defense Ministry said.
   At least 20 roads in the area were closed to traffic.
   The bomb was found 15 feet below ground in Whitechapel, an area
of London most famous for the five unsolved Jack the Ripper murders
of 1888.
   Bombs that were dropped during the war and failed to go off are
periodically unearthed in London. The Germans bombed the East End
especially heavily in a bid to cripple the docks there.
   The latest find was one of the largest bombs unearthed in recent
years.
</TEXT>
