<FIRST>r a AM-Cold-Animals     02-04 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold-Animals,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold And Drought Threaten Swans, Wind Stymies Bighorn Relocation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a quarter of the North American
population of trumpeter swans is in danger of starvation at their
winter feeding grounds in eastern Idaho, U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service officials say.
   Service biologist Signe Sather-Blair blames the 1988 drought and
current arctic cold for preventing the birds from getting their
normal food. They are not on the endangered species list, but they
are on Idaho's Sensitive Species list.
   The swans feed on aquatic plants, and low water in Henry's Fork
of the Snake River near Island Park has been frozen over. The
roughly 500 birds are unable to break through the ice to reach their
food.
   Elsewhere in Idaho, the cold and accompanying high wind has
interfered with state efforts to transplant bighorn sheep by
helicopter.
   In an attempt to rescue the swans, Fish and Wildlife was granted
1,600 acre-feet of water from irrigators in the Snake River Water
District and also received $8,000 from the Nature Conservancy to
purchase an additional 3,200 acre-feet of water.
   However, wildlife biologist Ruth Gail, who has studied the swans
for the Idaho Fish and Game Department, said Friday that the
increased water flow had not broken up the ice on the river.
   ``There is no way to measure what condition they are in now,''
Ms. Gail said of the swans. ``But it's pretty grim. They've had
decreased food supplies for 2{ months already this winter.''
   Ms. Gail said other swans, as many as 800, that water on lakes
and rivers around Yellowstone National Park may be in worse shape
than the flock at Henry's Fork.
   ``In all likelihood, we could lose a fair number of those
birds,'' she said. ``That's why it is so important to protect the
swans on the Henry's Fork.''
   The cold and high wind grounded the Idaho Department of Fish and
Game's plans to transplant bighorn sheep from the Morgan Creek
drainage north of Challis in central Idaho to the Selway River
drainage.
   Officials first attempted to capture sheep on Tuesday, ``but we
were blown out of the sky,'' Lloyd Oldenburg, the department's big
game supervisor, said Friday. He said it would be rescheduled for
the week of Feb. 12.
   He said two sheep were caught the first day but had to be
released once high winds kicked up and made flying difficult. Wind
and poor visibility also kept helicopters on the ground Wednesday.
   On Thursday, temperatures near zero, 10 mph wind and the
additional wind chill created by flying combined to create
temperatures estimated by Oldenburg at 100 degrees below zero.
   In addition, he said the net gun used to trap sheep froze and
would not fire, and the helicopter had no doors to protect the crew
from the cold.
   The lone ewe caught Thursday was released, but not before nasal,
blood and fecal samples were taken and a radio collar was placed on
her.
   Oldennburg said one of the sheep caught Tuesday, a 4-year-old
ram, appeared weak and in poor health, but he attributed that to two
years of drought and winter hardships rather than pneumonia. The
others appeared healthy, he said.
</TEXT>
