<FIRST>r a AM-BarricadedNuns     02-04 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barricaded Nuns,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesting Nuns Begin Fifth Month In Seclusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Carmelite nuns protesting
what they call the liberalization of their order began the fifth
month barricaded in their monastery's infirmary Saturday with no
apparent sign of coming out.
   Betty Sutton, a friend who acts as their spokeswoman, says the
five women are resigned to wait until the Vatican rules on their
dispute with monastery officials.
   ``They're patient and they're awaiting an answer and they're very
hopeful,'' she said in a telephone interview.
   Tim Manning, a spokesman for the Roman Catholic Diocese of
Paterson, said the nuns have given no sign of ending their protest.
   They are objecting to the introduction of such things as
television and candy into the monestery and want it returned to the
Carmelites' traditionally austere lifestyle. They also seek
permission to remain at the monestery.
   No word has come from the Vatican, and there is no way of knowing
when a decision can be expected, Manning said.
   ``Obviously, it must have been a very trying time for all the
nuns, those inside the infirmary and in the monastery,'' he said.
   There are eight other nuns at the Monastery of the Most Blessed
Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel.
   The nuns locked themselves in the infirmary Oct. 4, saying they
were afraid officials wanted to expel them from the monastery for
their dissident views.
   Since the protest began, vows of one of the five nuns, Sister
Bernadette, have expired, and those of another, Sister John of the
Cross, expire Feb. 19, Manning said. Those two were under temporary,
five-year vows while the other three's vows have become permanent.
   The nuns refuse to recognize the expiration dates, saying
everything remains status quo while their case is before the Vatican.
   Manning said the monastery will take no action against the two
nuns whose vows have expired or are expiring.
   ``The hope is that it will soon be resolved,'' he said.
</TEXT>
