<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-MafiaFiles     02-04 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mafia Files,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 13 Years, Mafia Commission Releases Files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most exhaustive Mafia study ever done by the
Italian government was released Saturday, 13 years after it was
completed, news reports said.
   The 3,852-page study lists the names of 2,405 people and 345
organizations or businesses collected by a special parliamentary
commission set up in 1962 to probe the Mafia, according to the ANSA
news agency and state-run television.
   The names range from well-known Italian politicians to such
fabled Mafiosi as Lucky Luciano, the Italian-American gangster, the
ANSA report said.
   ``The files published today don't refer to people suspected of
belonging to the Mafia or having links with it, but instead to every
person ... insinuated ... in a situation of this (Mafia) type,''
said the introduction written by Sen. Gerardo Chiaromonte, according
to ANSA.
   Chiaromonte is head of the current parliamentary anti-Mafia
commission.
   Sources for the names included police, newspaper reports,
witnesses who testified before the commission and anonymous tips.
   The report's release had been expected since Chiaromonte's
commission voted in November and again in December to make it public.
   No one answered the telephone in Chiaromonte's office Saturday,
and the Senate press office was closed.
   It was not clear whether the report would have much effect, both
because of its age and the varying credibility of the sources.
   Chiaromonte said the commission decided to make the list public
in order to dispel any suspicion that ``a public organism wants to
hide, in all or in part, news regarding the involvement of
politicians in Mafia affairs.''
   Links between politicians and the Mafia have been a hot topic
since the so-called ``maxi-trial'' ended in December 1987 with 338
people found guilty.
   The 30-member parliamentary commission issued statements listing
the names of some suspected Mafia leaders. But the final report did
not give names. The part made public called for trying suspected
organized crime figures on tax charges and increasing surveillance
of them.
   Leftist members of the commission, in a minority, had charged
that ``powder keg'' revelations were being covered up. But other
members of the commission said unsubstantiated charges should not be
published.
   The report released Saturday focuses on Mafia activity from 1963
to the early 1970s.
   It reportedly includes names of local and national politicians
ranging from communists to members of the far-right Italian
Socialist Movement.
   Among those denounced to the commission were several politicians,
judges and writers who had taken strong stands against the Mafia,
suggesting that some people tried to use the investigation to damage
their enemies.
   One senator who accused several politicians of having Mafia ties
was himself later charged by an anonymous source with having links
to the Mafia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890204-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GangSweep     02-04 0103</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gang Sweep,0104</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweep Nets 117 Arrests Guns, Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overnight anti-gang sweep by a police task
force resulted in the arrests of 117 people and the seizure of more
than 411 grams of cocaine, authorities said Saturday.
   The 14-hour sweep, which involved 242 officers and ended at 3
a.m. Saturday, was the latest in a series of sweeps that began last
year.
   Seventy-one of those arrested were alleged gang members, said
Teri Dixon of the police department's Training Division. There were
50 felony arrests, and police seized six guns and 411.5 grams of
cocaine, Ms. Dixon said.
</TEXT>
