<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-04 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Prepares For Crucial Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leaders met Saturday to prepare
for historic talks with the government that Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski called ``a significant event in the life of
Poland.''
   Lech Walesa and other leaders of the outlawed labor movement are
to sit down with government leaders on Monday to begin discussing
social and economic reforms considered crucial to this increasingly
impoverished nation.
   The long-awaited negotiations, known as the round-table talks,
will take place in Warsaw and also address the legalization of
Solidarity, the first recognized independent union in the East bloc.
   ``There was commotion concerning the round table in which I had
to take part as chief of government because I was aware of the fact
that the round table is a significant event in the life of Poland,''
Rakowski said in nationally televised address Saturday night.
   ``There may be advantages to all of us.''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said the opening session would
be aired on Polish television, the state-run news agency PAP
reported.
   In Gdansk, meanwhile, Solidarity's Citizen's Committee, which was
formed by Walesa in December to address social and political
problems, met to prepare for the talks.
   The names of the Solidarity delegates to the talks will be voted
on Sunday, said Solidarity spokesman Piotr Konopka.
   The government proposed the talks during a wave of strikes in
August, Poland's worst labor unrest since authorities imposed
martial law in December 1981.
   Walesa refused to agree to talks until the authorities agreed to
legalize the unionm which was banned by parliament in 1982.
   On Jan. 18, in a dramatic reversal of policy, the communist party
Central Committee said it would be willing to legalize the union if
its members agreed to obey the law, refrain from strikes and help
reform the economy.
   Walesa has said he agreed to bargain with authorities because of
the magnitude of Poland's problems.
   The offer has caused deep concern among the rank-and-file
communist party leadership, which concluded a three-day ideology
conference on Saturday.
   ``The conference confirmed that Marxism in Poland is at a stage
of difficult, but bold and unrestrained search,'' Politburo member
Marian Orzechowski said, PAP reported.
   Andrzej Czyz, head of the party's ideological department, said
the party would advocate political reform and the introduction of
greater freedom.
   ``The primary postulate was to speed the relinquishing of a
centrally governed society,'' Czyz said at a news conference.
</TEXT>
