<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Israel     02-04 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Israel,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt and Israel Agree to Resume Taba Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt and Israel will resume talks on the
disputed Taba border area Sunday and have agreed to try to resolve
all pending issues by early next month to expedite an Israeli
withdrawal, the Foreign Ministry said.
   ``The United States has told both sides that in its estimate, if
the two parties negotiate carefully and with good intentions, it
will be possible to end the negotiations in four weeks,'' said a
document signed Saturday by Nabil el-Araby, head of Egypt's Taba
delegation; Israeli ambassador Shamoun Shamir; and Frank Wisner, the
U.S. ambassador to Egypt.
   Washington is a partner in negotiations over the 250-acre patch
of beach overlooking the Gulf of Aqaba. It was awarded to Egypt by
international arbitrators Sept. 20.
   Egypt and Israel have twice set and broken deadlines to work out
Israel's withdrawal from Taba, leading to a stalemate the United
States has been trying to break.
   Three main issues block agreement: Egyptian compensation for an
Israeli-built luxury hotel and beach cabana complex; access for
Israelis to Taba; and location of the border line in the area where
tourist facilities are.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the talks would resume Sunday
between technical experts in Egypt and Israel. Teams in Cairo will
discuss compensation for the hotel and beach cabanas and those in
Hertzilia, Israel will negotiate Israelis' access to Taba.
   The ministry official said the Israeli withdrawal from Taba
should take only ``a few days'' once the pending issues are worked
out. The spokesman was not identified by name in accordance with
ministry instructions.
</TEXT>
