<FIRST>r a AM-DukakisSmear     02-04 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis Smear,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prosecutor to Plead Guilty in Trying to Smear Dukakis Aides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former county assistant prosecutor will plead
guilty to federal charges he manufactured evidence in an effort to
implicate top aides to Gov. Michael Dukakis in a drug case,
prosecution and defense attorneys said.
   Kevin J. Ross, 33, of Waltham plans to plead guilty Monday in
U.S. District Court to two charges: creating false documents and
making false statements, Kevin Sharkey, the federal prosecutor in
the case, told The Boston Globe in a report published Saturday.
   On each count, Ross faces up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine.
   Ross' attorney, Anthony R. Pelusi Jr., confirmed to the newspaper
that Ross would plead guilty. Pelusi did not return a telephone
message left Saturday by The Associated Press.
   According to court documents, Ross filled an address book with
the telephone numbers of key members of Dukakis' presidential
campaign and slipped it into a folder containing evidence seized
from the home of an alleged cocaine dealer.
   Among the names and numbers Ross allegedly wrote in the black
book were those of Dukakis presidential campaign chairman Paul
Brountas and fund-raiser Robert Farmer. But investigators say they
have found no evidence that Ross, a registered Republican, was part
of a politically motivated conspiracy.
   Ross was arrested in October and accused of planting the faked
address book.
   Ross later admitted entering into the book 35 of 71 names and
telephone numbers, including those of colleagues against whom he had
a grudge, Dukakis aides and reputed criminals Ross believed should
be brought to justice, the Globe reported.
   Investigators said that as part of the alleged scheme, Ross, a
former prosecutor in the Suffolk County district attorney's office,
called telephone numbers into the beeper the alleged dealer carried,
aiming to link those numbers, and the people with whom they were
listed, with the dealer.
   Ross was fired from his Suffolk County job after his arrest.
</TEXT>
