<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Rebel     02-04 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Rebel,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Rebel Leader Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a rebel leader at a hotel and
dealt a strong blow to Peru's pro-Cuban guerrilla movement,
authorities said Saturday.
   Police said Victor Polay, 37, was seized with a female companion
late Friday in Huancayo, 140 miles east of Lima.
   Polay, a former college friend of President Alan Garcia, is
considered one of the leaders of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement, which favors Cuba-styled Marxism. The group began armed
actions against the government in 1984.
   The seizure of Polay, known as Commander Rolando, is the most
important guerrilla arrest since Osman Morote, the reputed No. 2
leader of the Maoist Shining Path guerrilla band, was captured in
June, said police.
   They spoke on condition of anonymity, citing security reasons.
   The Tupac Amaru group is smaller and considered much less violent
than the Shining Path, whose nine-year insurgency has claimed more
than 12,000 lives. The two groups do not have ties.
   Dozens of police surrounded the hotel where Polay was staying and
arrested him without a struggle. Police refused to say how they knew
he was at the hotel.
   The Lima newspaper Expreso said Polay shouted ``Death to
informers!'' as he was led away.
   The Tupac Amaru guerrillas startled Peru in November 1987 when
Polay led 100 well-armed rebels in a monthlong series of raids near
Tarapoto, a jungle city 435 miles northeast of Lima.
   The military quickly dispersed the rebel column. The government
never fully disclosed details of the clashes, but analysts said the
rebel band was seriously hurt. Its armed actions since have been
rare.
   In the 1960s, Polay was a student leader of the governing
center-left Aprista Party. He reportedly studied with Garcia in
Europe in the early 1970s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
