<DOCNO> AP890204-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Kenosha-Chrysler     02-04 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenosha-Chrysler,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Donates Several Buildings To Kenosha, To Demolish Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has donated several abandoned
buildings to the community before tearing down most of its former
car assembly plant here, officials said.
   The company, whose auto assembly lines in Kenosha were closed in
December, announced Friday that some structures would remain for use
by the city, county and Gateway Technical College.
   John Collins, the Kenosha County executive administrator, said
Chrysler wanted to raze all the main plant buildings except for an
engine factory and stamping operation, but local officials persuaded
it to donate some buildings.
   Richard Dauch, Chrysler's vice president of manufacturing, said
the donations represent about 550,000 square feet of office and
factory space in four buildings. In addition, some land near a
municipal golf course will be deeded to the city of 80,000
residents, he said.
   The plant's main office building will be donated to Kenosha
County for its Social Services Department, officials said. Collins
said officials plan to move the Wisconsin Job Service into the
building to create a central location for former Chrysler workers
seeking welfare and job-hunting help.
   Dauch said a factory building will be turned over to Gateway Tech
for a business incubator center. A nearby building will be donated
for the school's administrative offices. Kenosha Area Development
Corp. will move into a fourth building.
   Chrysler obtained the factory complex as part of its 1987
purchase of American Motors Corp. The complex had been used for
automaking for 86 years.
   Chrysler announced in January 1988 that it would shut down most
of the plant, citing its age and inefficiency.
   Wisconsin officials threatened to sue Chrysler, saying the
automaker had promised verbally to keep the plant open through 1992
in exchange for $5 million in state job training funds.
   Chrysler reached an out-of-court settlement that included $250
million in aid to workers, the community of nearly 80,000 residents
and the state.
   About 4,500 jobs were lost last year when Chrysler closed the
factory except for engine production.
   The company's 1.8-million-square-feet engine plant, which employs
1,350 workers, will remain in operation, Dauch said. The company
also will retain ownership of several parking lots and a shipping
yard, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
