<DOCNO> AP890204-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Chess     02-04 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Chess,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Game In Timman-Portisch Match Adjourned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fourth game in the World Chess
Championship Candidates quarterfinal between Holland's Jan Timman
and Hungary's Lajos Portisch was adjourned after 62 moves Saturday.
   The bishops and pawns left on the board after six hours of play
might still hide some surprises but experts felt a draw would be the
most likely outcome.
   Dutch grandmaster John van der Wiel, who visited the tournament
hall in the basement of an Antwerp luxury hotel to see his
countryman in action, even said he expected the two opponents would
sign the draw without further play.
   ``Of course, Timman will analyze the position thoroughly with his
seconds overnight, but I for one don't see how he could possibly
avoid splitting the point with Portisch in this one,'' Van der Wiel
said.
   A draw would be a serious setback for the 37-year-old Timman, who
played white in Saturday's game and desperately needed a victory to
catch up with his 51-year-old Hungarian opponent.
   Portisch won the third encounter the day before and was leading
2-1 with only two more games to go in the six-game match, one of a
series of knock-out contests to select a challenger who will play
world champion Gary Kasparov for his title in 1990.
   Timman started the game well, following a line from the Ruy Lopez
to build up a better position and concentrating his forces on the
queenside, where he seemed set to launch a strong offensive.
   At the decisive moment, however, he hesitated, playing a number
of careful moves, when he might have pressed his advantage and start
an all-out offensive.
   Portisch reacted immediately, exchanging queens and, after some
tactical complications, getting the rooks off the board as well.
   Even Timman's West German second, Vlastimil Hort, admitted the
Hungarian was ``playing a fine defending game'' at that stage.
   ``Portisch kept a cool head'', he said. ``Jan's attack seemed
decisive, but maybe Portisch had calculated farther and decided he
could take the risk.''
   ``Jan was probably right in not going all out. In fact, I think
it's a miracle the way he is playing, especially after the defeat he
suffered yesterday. Most players would not even try. They would
settle for a draw the day after they lost a game,'' Hort said.
   Public attention for the duel was overwhelming at first, with
about one hundred spectators watching in the silence of the
tournament hall, while another two hundred thronged the auditorium
next door, where two Belgian masters, Richard Meulders and Luc
Winants, were commenting on the game _ Meulders in Flemish and
Winants in French.
   But after Portisch had succeeded in maintaining the balance and
the game developed into an ever more drawish position, most people
went home until only a handful were left to see Portisch seal his
move at the 62nd.
   The resumption is to be played on Sunday with the fifth game
following on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
