<FIRST>r a AM-Thornburgh1stLd-Writethru a0565   02-04 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Regulator Cannot Offer Immunity, Thornburgh Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with speech; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Saturday he
has told regulators with the Federal Home Loan Bank Board ``in no
uncertain terms'' that they lack authority to promise immunity from
prosecution to savings and loan officials.
   ``Henceforth it's not to be indulged in,'' Thornburgh said. The
attorney general said he believed there were only ``isolated
instances'' in which bank board regulators offered immunity from
prosecution to those under investigation for fraud in the savings
and loan industry.
   Thornburgh, in an impromptu news conference following a luncheon
speech at the American Bar Association convention here, declined to
be drawn into a possible controversy over gun control.
   ABA President Robert Raven said Friday he asked Thornburgh to
support a federal waiting period for would-be gun buyers.
   Raven, citing the recent slaying of five children at a Stockton,
Calif., school and the wounding of four others in Washington, D.C.,
said there is a ``glaring loophole'' in federal law that allows
people to buy automatic weapons and assault rifles.
   Thornburgh refused to say if he supports Raven's waiting period
proposal or if such weapons are too easily purchased.
   ``We want to look at it,'' the attorney general said.
   The savings and loan questions were prompted by a reports that
federal prosecutors are being hamstrung by promises of immunity made
by Home Loan Bank Board regulators.
   A U.S. attorney in Los Angeles said top officials of the failed
San Marino Savings &amp; Loan Corp. were told they could avoid
prosecution by helping regulators recover some of the money lost
when the thrift institution collapsed in 1984.
   Thornburgh said the offer was a misunderstanding made without
consultation with the Justice Department and that bank board
regulators have been warned not to do it again.
   Thornburgh also met with the ABA group that assesses judicial
appointees and said he thinks it will continue to play a role in
evaluating Bush administration nominees to the federal bench.
   In his remarks to the ABA luncheon, Thornburgh said the Bush
administration will be a tough fighter against street crime.
   ``Firm and effective action against drug-related criminal
activities, including application of the newly enacted federal death
penalty, will be necessary to end the free-fire zones that have
taken the lives of so many innocent people,'' he said.
   Thornburgh also said he supports a pay raise of about 50 percent
for federal judges that is due to take effect unless both houses of
Congress vote to block it before Wednesday.
   ``It's absolutely essential that the pay-raise bill take
effect,'' he said.
   Thornburgh also said he will press for higher pay for U.S.
attorneys and FBI agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
