<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Amnesty     02-04 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Amnesty,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Soviets Invite Amnesty International</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International, which has been trying for
decades to get into the Soviet Union to investigate human rights
abuses, has been invited for a visit, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   Officials of the London-based human rights organization were not
available to confirm the report in the Guardian. The paper said the
group had written to Moscow to discuss the timing of the visit and
the range of people and institutions with whom contacts would be
sought.
   Amnesty International has been seeking an invitation to the
Soviet Union since 1960, when the organization was established, the
Guardian said.
   In December, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev declared his
government no longer held political prisoners, and Western observers
generally acknowledge a dramatic drop in the number of political
prisoners since Gorbachev rose to power.
   Amnesty International said in October that it had information on
150 Soviets ``imprisoned solely for the non-violent exercise of
their fundamental human rights.''
   The human rights group said its list included about 30 religious
believers, 30 conscientious objectors to military service and about
20 people held against their will for indefinite periods in
psychiatric hospitals.
   It also said it had information that since February 1987, 314
political prisoners had been released in the Soviet Union, ``249 of
whom we knew or suspected to have been prisoners of conscience.''
</TEXT>
