<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Follies     02-04 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Follies,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Running Musical Has Gala Finish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first London production of ``Follies,'' Stephen
Sondheim's 1971 musical, came to a gala finish Saturday after a
19-month run that won extensive critical acclaim but made no money.
   ``You are seeing the last night of my dream to bring ``Follies''
to London,'' producer Cameron Mackintosh told the audience at the
conclusion of a performance marked by nostalgia, affection and
repeated ovations.
   Mackintosh gave special thanks to American director Harold Prince
``for putting it on in the first place.''
   His remarks ended a 10-minute standing ovation that also brought
onto the stage composer-lyricist Sondheim and the musical's
choreographer Bob Avian, both of whom had flown in from New York for
the evening.
   The musical at the Shaftesbury Theater told the story of two
former Follies showgirls and the stage-door Johnnies they married,
all of whom reconvene at a party in 1970 inside a Broadway theater
earmarked for demolition.
   At its July 21, 1987, bow, the London production starred Julia
McKenzie, Diana Rigg, David Healy, and Daniel Massey, with veteran
American performer Dolores Gray in the supporting role of Carlotta,
who sings the showstopper, ``I'm Still Here.''
   Directed by Mike Ockrent (``Me and My Girl'') and produced by
Cameron Mackintosh, the musical boasted four new songs by Sondheim
and a somewhat more upbeat finish from the original, which ended
with one character having a nervous breakdown.
   The new ``Follies'' was chosen Best Musical of 1987 at all three
of London's theater awards ceremonies.
   Three of the five principals stayed with the show throughout its
run. In July, Millicent Martin replaced Diana Rigg and Eartha Kitt
took over from Dolores Gray in a casting coup that has led to Kitt's
upcoming concert show at the same theater, starting March 13.
   One commentator, Brian Hunt in The Daily Telegraph, used the
closing of ``Follies'' to strike out Saturday at what he called
Sondheim's ``inflated reputation.''
   ``With Sondheim, we get all the glitter and glamor and still
remain aloof,'' wrote Hunt in an article entitled ``The trouble with
Stephen Sondheim.'' He said that ``In 13 musicals, only two songs
stand out as being beautiful and original.''
   Budgeted at $2.8 million, ``Follies'' repaid 60 percent of its
investment and was never the sellout smash of such other
Mackintosh-produced musicals as ``Les Miserables'' and ``The Phantom
of the Opera.''
   Despite winning seven Tony Awards, the original Broadway
engagement failed to recoup its investment which, at $800,000, was
hefty at the time.
   Present hopes are for a recast American production of ``Follies''
to start a national tour in the fall. No actors have been signed,
although Julie Andrews and Barbara Cook have been touted for the two
leading roles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890204-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Massacre     02-04 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Massacre,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces New Investigation of Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army will reopen an
investigation into the massacre of 10 peasants, this time with a
panel that will not include the commander of the brigade accused of
the killings, officials said Saturday.
   Col. Emilio Chavez Caceres, commander of the 5th Army brigade in
San Vicente Province, played a key role in the initial investigation
that absolved his soldiers of responsibility in the killings last
year.
   The decision to reopen the investigation followed a Friday
meeting between the high command and visiting Vice President Dan
Quayle, who said the Bush administration is concerned about an
upswing in political violence in El Salvador, said a military
officer, who commented on condition of anonymity.
   A senior U.S. official who attended meetings during Quayle's
visit said the vice president hinted that if human rights conditions
are not improved, Washington may withhold some of the $400 million
in aid to the country.
   ``What does he have to say? No convictions (of implicated
officers), no money? That's too blunt. But there was no question he
was talking about aid,'' said the U.S. official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   El Salvador, a tiny country of 5.5 million people, has received
more than $3.5 billion in economic and military aid this decade _
more than any country in the Western Hemisphere. The aid is part of
the U.S. effort to help the government combat a 9-year-old leftist
insurgency.
   The army officer said the new investigation would be conducted by
a panel of high-ranking military officers.
   ``Rather than presuming innocence, the investigators will presume
guilt and those implicated will have to show they did not commit the
abuses,'' he said.
   On Sept. 21, soldiers of the 5th brigade's Jiboa Battalion
rounded up the residents of the hamlet of San Francisco, 27 miles
east of San Salvador and accused them of collaborating with rebels.
Seven men and three women were marched away and shots were heard in
the distance, according to witnesses.
   Forensic examinations showed the 10 were killed by point-blank
shots to the head.
   The army first claimed the ten were guerrillas killed in combat
but later said guerrillas attacked while the 10 were being marched
away. This version of the incident was upheld by the investigation
in which the soldiers' brigade commander took part.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
