<FIRST>r a AM-Husband-Guardian     02-04 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Husband-Guardian,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband Seeking Abortion For Comatose Wife Says She Would Approve</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPER BROOKVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who is seeking a
court-sanctioned abortion for his comatose wife said Saturday he
believes she would approve of his actions.
   Martin Klein, 34, of Upper Brookville is awaiting a decision on
his petition seeking appointment as his wife's legal guardian so he
can authorize an abortion that he and some doctors say could help
her survive.
   ``It's been stressful,'' Klein said. ``It's been very
frustrating. I am doing what my wife would want me to do.''
   ``Inside they have ripped my guts out,'' he added. ``But my wife
deserves every chance she is entitled to, and I am going to do
everything in my power to see that she gets it.''
   Klein's 32-year-old wife, Nancy, is 17 weeks pregnant. She has
been in a coma at North Shore University Hospital in Manhassett
since she was injured in a car accident Dec. 13.
   The hospital refused to allow an abortion for Mrs. Klein unless
her husband is named her legal guardian.
   State Supreme Court Justice Bernard McCaffrey reserved a decision
Thursday on the case, described as unprecedented by legal and
medical experts, after a two-day hearing that drew supporters and
opponents of abortion.
   Klein, an accountant, said he had hoped the decision would be a
private one, as do his wife's parents, who support the decision to
terminate the pregnancy.
   ``We didn't want any publicity,'' said Klein, saying that if his
wife knew what was happening she, too, would be uncomfortable about
it.
   ``She is a very private kind of person,'' he said. ``I just want
to get the court order safe in my hands so we can at least resolve
one issue and get it behind us.''
   During the hearing, five medical experts for Klein testified that
pregnancy decreases the chances of recovery for the comatose patient
and could threaten her life.
   However, two other experts called by the Nassau County district
attorney testified that the pregnancy was not life-threatening. The
district attorney said he entered the case, in part, to ensure that
an abortion was not performed without consent.
   Klein visits his wife daily. She suffered extensive brain damage
and has been unconscious since the accident, but is not on
life-support machines.
   ``I talk to her,'' he said. ``I work with her arms and legs _
it's important that they don't get stiff. ... I just have to take
one day at a time.'' He said he has seen a slight improvement in his
wife's condition.
   The couple have a 3-year-old daughter, Arielle.
   ``For right now, I have to be strong for my family, my daughter
and my wife,'' Klein said.
   ``If I don't hold up, what will be left?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
