<FIRST>r a AM-ColdBus 2ndLd-Writethru a0596 02-04 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold Bus, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0596,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riders Get Frostbite On Long Bus Ride</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to change to Greyhound sted Greyhound Trailways per
company's style; SUBS grafs 6-8, `The passengers ...,' with 7 grafs to
UPDATE with Greyhound saying offer to switch to heated bus made 4 times,
picking up 9th graf, `Clark said ...'; INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf,
``I'm cold ...,' with Greyhound denying 2nd bus was cold, company investigating
incident, picking up last graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people were treated for frostbite and
hypothermia after a 500-mile journey in below-zero weather on an
unheated Greyhound bus, a passenger and hospital spokeswoman said.
   ``If it hadn't been for my blankets, I think we'd be in worse
condition than we are now,'' said Dan Clark of Missoula, Mont., who
said his daughter was treated for frostbite at St. Luke's
Hospitals-MeritCare after they arrived here Friday on the bus from
Billings, Mont.
   Deb Nelson, a hospital nursing supervisor, identified the child
Saturday as 4-year-old Janilynn. A total of five people from the bus
were treated for cold-related maladies and later released, according
to another supervisor, who declined to identify herself.
   The Forum newspaper of Fargo quoted one passenger as saying he
blacked out for a half-hour from hypothermia. He declined to
identify himself, the newspaper reported Saturday.
   Dale Bruggeman, a Greyhound supervisor in Fargo, said Saturday
that the bus' alternator failed at Forsyth, Mont., about 100 miles
east of Billings and 500 miles from Fargo. The malfunction left the
bus essentially without heat, he said.
   George Gravley, a spokesman at Greyhound Lines Inc.'s
headquarters in Dallas, said the 33 original passengers were invited
to transfer to a heated bus on four separate occasions along the
route.
   The first offer was made at Miles City, Mont., about 50 miles
east of Forsyth, Gravley said. The heated bus waited there for the
cold bus, 15 passengers transferred to it, and both buses traveled
together to Fargo, he said.
   Another five transferred 75 miles later at Glendive, Mont., he
said. After Glendive, the heated bus had standing room only, he
said, adding that no other buses were available.
   The third and fourth offers to transfer were made in Dickinson
and Sterling in North Dakota, but no one accepted, he said.
   ``That was their choice, stand on the warm bus or sit on the cold
bus,'' he said.
   Three passengers on the cold bus completed their trip and got off
at Bismarck, leaving 10 who arrived in Fargo on the cold bus,
Gravley said. He also said the driver had the authority to stop at
any time, but passengers did not protest and some maintained that
they were ``tough'' and urged the driver to continue.
   Bruggeman said some riders even wanted to move from the heated
bus to the cold one.
   Clark said the bus he took from Missoula to Billings also had no
heat.
   ``I'm cold and sick, and I'm going to have to tough it out,''
said Clark, who said he was returning to Fort Wayne, Ind., after
losing his truck-driving job in Missoula.
   Gravley denied that the second bus had a heating problem.
   The company is conducting an internal investigation into the
matter, he said.
   Billings' cold continued Saturday, hitting a record low of 22
degrees below zero.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890204-0151 </DOCNO>
