<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Chess     02-04 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chess,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yusupov Defeats Spraggett In Sudden Death Playoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artur Yusupov of the Soviet Union scored a
brilliant victory over Canada's Kevin Spraggett in a sudden-death
playoff Saturday to win their World Chess Championship Candidates
quarterfinal and advance to the semifinal stage.
   With both players' thinking time limited to one hour each for the
entire game, Yusupov, playing black, unleashed a dazzling queen
sacrifice on his 28th move to gain a crushing attack with his
remaining pieces against Spraggett's King.
   ``It was the best move in all the match.'' said Yves Boisvert, a
Canadian chess commentator.
   As Yusupov steadied his nerves and waited to deliver an
unstoppable checkmate on his 51st move, Spraggett ran out of time
and lost the game.
   ``I'm not disappointed. I lost, but I think I gave it my best,''
Spraggett told reporters at a joint news conference with his
opponent onstage at the playing hall in Quebec's Gabrielle-Roy
Library.
   Yusupov said Spraggett had proved his equal by holding him to a
4-4 tie over the eight games played before Saturday at a slower rate.
   After his victory, Yusupov rushed from the hall to tell his wife,
Tatiana, of the victory. Following Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of
glasnost, wives of Soviet Grandasters have, in the last months,
begun to travel to the west with their husbands.
   When the players came back to the stage, they received a standing
ovation of more than a minute from the disappointed, but
appreciative Canadian crowd.
   The winner of the Candidates, a series of knockout matches, will
challenge world champion Garri Kasparov for his title in 1990.
   Yusupov, a 28-year-old Muscovite joins British Grandmaster
Jonathan Speelman in the semifinals.
   Mark Dvoretsky, a Soviet international master who acts as
Yusupov's second, said Yusupov would probably play former world
champion and fellow Soviet Anatoly Karpov in the semifinals.
   Karpov is currently leading Iceland's Johann Hjartarson 3-1 in
the six-game duel underway in Seattle, and requires only one draw
from two games to win the contest.
   Speelman is likely to meet either Lajos Portisch of Hungary or
Dutch Grandmaster Jan Timman. Portisch is leading their contest in
Antwerp, Belgium 2-1 after three games.
   Robert Finta, the general director of the Quebec Chess Federation
who oragnized the contest with the support of Quebec's provincial
government said the players would split the $42,000 prize fund
becasue the match was tied after the initial six games.
   Both semifinals will be staged together in London in the autumn.
Each contest wil feature a prize $125,000, with five-eighths to the
winner and three-eighths for the loser.
   In a remarakable incident at the 1983 Candidates quarterfinal
between Robert Huebner of West Germany and former world champion
Vassily Smyslov of the Soviet Union in Velden Austria, organizers
turned to the roulettte table to break the tie.
   Huebner refused to attend, and on the first spin, the ball landed
on the zero.
   But on the second roll, the ball landed on red and gave Smyslov
victory. He went on to reach the Candidates final before being
knockout out by Kasparov.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
