<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-US     02-04 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-US,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker and Sihanouk Exchange Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, in an exchange of letters with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, has called on the United States to step up its efforts to
resolve the Cambodian conflict.
   ``We Cambodian patriots ask the United States to play a more
important and active role in the search for a fair solution to the
problem of Cambodia,'' Sihanouk said in his letter dated Friday and
seen Sunday.
   Sihanouk said he received the Baker letter earlier in the day
during a meeting with U.S. Ambassador to China Winston Lord. The
meeting took place at Beijing's state guesthouse, where Sihanouk is
staying.
   According to a copy of the Baker letter provided by Sihanouk,
Baker expressed U.S. ``appreciation for your indispensable
leadership in the valiant struggle of the Cambodian people to regain
their independence.''
   Baker said, ``without question, your leadership is crucial to
achieving an acceptable Cambodian settlement, both as the head of an
interim government preceding elections and as a symbol and focus for
the unity of your people.
   ``We consider it vital that you remain involved in the ongoing
diplomatic processes, and that your views be conveyed to all
involved parties at every opportunity.''
   Sihanouk leads one of three China-backed forces fighting
Vietnamese troops in Cambodia. China and the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) want Sihanouk to head a coalition
government to take power after Vietnam's pullout, tentatively set
for September.
   The prince is thought to be the only man with broad enough
support to unify his nation, but his unpredictable diplomatic ploys
have also complicated efforts to resolve the conflict. He has on
several occasions resigned as president of the three-party
resistance government because of differences with his coalition
partners.
   Last month he announced he would boycott all further peace talks
because Hun Sen, prime minister of the Vietnam-backed government in
Phnom Penh, had rejected his proposals for introducing an
international peacekeeping force after Vietnam ends its 10-year
occupation.
   He has since modified his position, saying he will support any
unanimous agreements coming out of talks in Jakarta, Indonesia later
this month among the warring factions.
   Sihanouk was ousted in a 1970 coup he alleged was engineered by
the CIA. However, his faction now receives non-military aid from the
United States, which calls for an end to the Vietnamese occupation
and the holding of free elections in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
