<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     02-04 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems Protest Rushdie Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 3,000 Moslems marched in this
central English city Saturday to protest the book ``The Satanic
Verses,'' which they consider blasphemous.
   Demonstrators from around the country marched from Central Mosque
to Chamberlain Square in the city center, where they heard speeches
from religious leaders and delivered a protest petition to city hall.
   West Midlands police estimated the number of marchers at 3,000
and said the protest was peaceful.
   India and some Arab nations have banned Salman Rushdie's ``The
Satanic Verses,'' which is named after the verses the Prophet
Mohammed removed from the Koran _ the Islamic holy book _ on grounds
they were inspired by the devil.
   Copies have been burned at protests in the northern city of
Bradford, which has a large Moslem population, and last week
demonstrators marched in London and vowed to take legal action over
its publication.
   Indian-born Rushdie describes ``The Satanic Verses'' as a moral
parable about contemporary Britain and India.
   It has been a best-seller in Britain, won the Whitbread Novel
Award in 1988 and was runner-up for the prestigious Booker Prize.
</TEXT>
