<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Protests     02-04 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protests,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>March Against Rightists' Election Success; Right-wingers Draw Counter-Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-German Right, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto HBG1</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands marched through West Berlin on Saturday
to protest policies of a radical right-wing political party that won
seats in a local election. In the northern city of Rotenberg,
right-wing demonstrators drew counter-protesters.
   ``Nazis Out of West Berlin!'' and ``Foreigners stay _ Nazis
away!''chanted protesters in the crowd estimated at nearly 10,000,
in the peaceful afternoon procession along Berlin's famed
Kurfuerstendamm.
   A right-wing extremist party, the Republicans, campaigned on an
arch-conservative platform that included a call to oust foreign
workers from the city.
   The party won 7.5 percent of the Berlin vote in ballotting last
Sunday, giving it 11 seats in the local parliament and the right to
send two representatives to the federal Bundestag next year.
   Their positions won broader support than pollsters predicted,
reflecting the volatile and growing nationalist sentiments stirred
by housing and job shortages that are especially acute in West
Berlin.
   However, moderate and left-wing supporters have staged a number
of protests against the Republicans and their policies since the
surprising election outcome.
   In Rotenburg near Bremen, 200 right-wing supporters demonstrated
for the the Free German Workers Party, drawing a counter-protest by
1,200 opponents. Four hundred police officers kept the displays
reasonably peaceful, with only one minor injury from a thrown rock
reported.
