<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-S&amp;Ls 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 02-04 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-S&amp;Ls, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0603,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Advisers Confer on S&amp;L Crisis; No Decision Reached</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``The plan...'' to
add details; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``White House...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and top advisers conferred for
more than 3{ hours on the savings and loan crisis Saturday, but the
president made no decisions, the White House said.
   The advisers _ including Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady,
Budget Director Richard Darman and Chief of Staff John Sununu _
traveled to the president's Camp David, Md., retreat for a working
session from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m., said B. Jay Cooper, a presidential
spokesman.
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan joined the group
for lunch, which broke up shortly after 2:30 p.m.
   ``Options were presented to the president. He made no decisions
at the meeting,'' Cooper said.
   Among proposals that were to have been presented to the president
were plans to raise $54 billion over three years through complicated
financing arrangements based largely on boosting deposit insurance
premiums paid by the institution, according to a report Saturday in
The New York Times.
   The plan would call for banks to pay 18 cents in insurance
premiums for every $100 in deposits, while savings and loans would
pay 25 cents per $100, according to unnamed congressional aides
cited by the newspaper. Banks currently pay 8 cents per $100 in
deposits, while S&amp;Ls pay 21 cents.
   Also, the Times' Sunday editions quoted industry officials as
saying the Bush administration is studying a proposal to take
control of the 350 insolvent savings and loan associations and place
them under the management of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   Advocates argue that the FDIC, with 4,000 bank liquidators and a
reputation for toughness, would be better able to bring the problem
under control than the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which has a
smaller staff and is less experienced, the Times said.
   Member of the Home Loan Bank Board, which oversees S&amp;Ls, and the
FDIC chairman would have to approve the plan, but it would not take
an act of Congress, the Times said.
   The General Accounting Office on Thursday urged the government to
consider taking over the insolvent S&amp;Ls once an overall bailout plan
is devised.
   White House aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Friday that a controversial fee paid by bank and S&amp;L depositors
likely would not be a part of the package.
   Bush met with industry officials on Thursday and congressional
leaders Friday and said he would lay out his plan early this week.
He plans to include the subject in a nationally broadcast speech to
Congress on Thursday.
</TEXT>
