<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Shevardnadze     02-04 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Shevardnadze,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Arrives For Talks With Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze arrived here early Sunday for talks on Afghanistan as
the Red Army headed home after nine years of intervention in the
country's civil war.
   Shevardnadze said he would conduct ``intense negotiations'' with
Pakistani officials before his departure Sunday afternoon, but he
did not respond to reporters' questions on whether he would meet
with Pakistan-based guerrilla leaders.
   His visit capped a week of diplomatic efforts to bring
Afghanistan's warring factions to terms as Moscow prepares to pull
all its troops out by Feb. 15, ending a massive military involvement
that began in December 1979 to prop up the Marxist government in
Kabul.
   With the last units reportedly on their way home, there still are
no prospects for peace between the Kabul government and guerrillas
armed by the United States and Pakistan.
   ``The Soviet leadership has decided to consult with the
government of Pakistan on how best to contribute to restoring peace
and tranquility in Afghanistan,'' Shevardnadze told reporters on his
arrival at Islamabad airport.
   ``Problems have been piling up. There are quite a few of them,''
he said, speaking through an interpreter.
   Prince Sadruddin Agha Khan, head of the United Nations' relief
effort for Afghanistan, arrived in the Pakistani capital Saturday
with an appeal to Afghan combatants to ``give peace a chance.''
   He told reporters at the airport that he would meet with
Pakistani officials and Pakistan-based guerrilla leaders, then later
fly to Kabul to coordinate an airlift of emergency food and other
supplies to beleagured Afghan cities.
   Soviet forces entered Afghanistan in 1979 to replace one Marxist
government with another. They agreed to withdraw under a
U.N.-brokered accord.
</TEXT>
