<FIRST>r a AM-UkraineGirl     02-04 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukraine Girl,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Teen Placed On Waiting List For Heart-Lung Transplant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old girl from the Soviet Ukraine has
been found to fit the medical criteria for a heart-lung transplant,
officials said.
   Oksansa Klebkyna's name will be placed on a waiting list for
donor organs at the Arizona Heart Institute here, the officials said.
   She arrived here several weeks ago to see if American doctors
could repair her heart, which has been defective since birth.
   Doctors at the institute said Thursday the chambers of her heart
were malformed and that only a heart-lung transplant could save her
life. Doctors said her lungs had been irreparably damaged by years
of extremely high blood pressure.
   Dr. Edward Diethrich and Humana Hospital Phoenix have agreed to
donate the surgery.
   Heart-lung donations can only come from brain-dead patients on
life-sustaining machines, doctors said, adding that the donor would
have be about the same physical size as the girl and have a
compatible immune system and blood type.
</TEXT>
