<FILEID>AP-NR-02-04-89 2334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MardiGras 1stLd-Writethru a0592 02-04 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mardi Gras, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Biggest Free Party in World' Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with parades, injury, quote. Picks
up 5th graf, `Some roisterers ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parade-watchers and party-goers bundled up
Saturday against a suddenly cold Carnival weekend, the start of a
four-day spectacle expected to draw nearly 2 million merrymakers by
Mardi Gras.
   Nine parades rolled Saturday in metropolitan New Orleans,
including the extravagant Endymion with huge floats and celebrity
riders such as Fred Savage, the child television star of ``The
Wonder Years,'' and pop singers Daryl Hall and John Oates.
   New Orleans police estimated this will be the biggest Mardi Gras
ever, with 1.7 million revelers lining the streets and jamming the
French Quarter on Fat Tuesday, the last blowout before the solemn
season of Lent. Authorities said 1.5 million people attended the
1988 celebration.
   Police reported few problems during the parades Saturday, which
drew thousands of revelers. The lone injury was a float rider who
required stitches after she was hit in the head by an undetermined
object during an all-women's parade.
   The day was cloudy, cold and damp, with temperatures in the 40s
and chilling winds. The National Weather Service said an arctic air
mass would drop temperatures into the 30s through Tuesday, but that
didn't deter Saturday night's parade-stalkers.
   ``The crowd is really just as big as normal. As long as it
doesn't rain, they'll come out,'' said Hilda Ramsey, desk clerk at
the Hummingbird Hotel, along the Endymion route.
   Some roisterers sought internal and external warmth in bars along
oak-lined St. Charles Avenue, a major parade route.
   ``They're here anyway and they're going to go drinking,'' said
Matt Hendricks at Fat Harry's. ``Instead of standing outside, it
just gets packed inside. The cold weather makes no difference.''
   For others visitors, there were worse things to deal with than
the damp, winter weather _ the city's notorious hard-line parking
regulations and always-ready tow trucks.
   ``I thought my car was stolen,'' said Jeff Jacob of Memphis,
Tenn., whose rental car was town away before a parade earlier this
week.
   ``But after they checked the license, they told me, `We have it.'
I couldn't believe it,'' he said.
   The New Orleans Streets Department begins towing two hours before
parade time. Signs in Carnival colors of purple, green and gold
alert drivers to the financial hazards of blocking parade routes.
   For some University of Florida students, the problem wasn't cars,
it was hotel space.
   When 10 buses from Gainesville pulled up to the Days Inn in
suburban Kenner on Friday, nearly 200 of the 600 students learned
they didn't have a place to sleep.
   ``We had all made our commitments to come here _ paid the travel
agency for everything in full,'' said student Bill McClure. ``But
somewhere along the way, somebody screwed up.''
   Five hours later, Days Inn Manager Robert Murphy and Gator Travel
owners Jim and John Fahlen found 15 rooms to handle 60 students,
while the rest were put in rooms that already held two students each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
