<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv04-05   02-04 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 04-05,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Feb. 4-5</HEAD>
<HEAD>Credit Markets Preparing For Quarterly Auction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department will be turning to the
auction block again soon to peddle a barrage of new bonds and notes
that will help support the government's growing national debt.
   This time around, Wall Street's largest brokers will be asked to
buy $28.75 billion in new three- and 10-year notes and 30-year
bonds. They, in turn, will resell the securities to the public.
   Analysts said the auction plan outlined this past week was in
line with market expectations. It's set to begin Tuesday and end
Thursday.
   The only big difference between this auction and the previous two
is that it includes the 30-year bond, which was on hiatus because
Congress had failed to raise the ceiling on issuance of long-term
debt. Congress finally passed new legislation before it adjourned
last year.
   While there were few surprises in the size of the upcoming sale,
economists appeared divided on how well it might go in the wake of
the latest economic data.
   Adding pressure to the credit markets was the government's
January unemployment report, which pointed to continued strength in
the economy along with the possibility of higher inflation.
   The report, released Friday, showed that the nation's jobless
rate inched up to 5.4 percent in January from 5.3 percent at the end
of the year. But despite the slight increase, 408,000 new jobs were
created last month, and that was far more than most economists had
predicted.
   ``We believe the employment data is extremely negative,'' said
William V. Sullivan, director of money market research for Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It increases the pressures for the Fed to
tighten credit.''
   The Federal Reserve has indicated repeatedly that it will push
for higher interest rates to keep inflation in check, thereby making
borrowing more expensive and slowing down economic growth.
   Sullivan and several other analysts predict that interest rates
will be on the rise going into the upcoming auction.
   ``We don't think the current yield level reflects the underlying
fundamentals in the U.S. economy,'' he said.
   The upward slant in rates will put pressure on the Treasury to
make the yields of its new bonds and notes high enough to attract
domestic and foreign money.
   One saving grace, though, is the fact that the dollar has
remained strong in foreign exchange.
   ``The foreign exchange market is definitely a plus for the
Treasury auction,'' said Carol A. Stone, a senior economist for
Nomura Securities International Inc. ``I would say there will be
good foreign participation.''
   A rising dollar is seen as good news for foreigners because it
means they are likely to earn more on their dollar-denominated
investments.
   Proceeds of the upcoming Treasury auction will be used toward
raising about $13.7 billion in cash and redeeming $15.1 billion in
old obligations, which make up part of the $2.8 trillion national
debt.
   The sale will begin on Tuesday with $9.75 billion worth of
three-year notes, followed by $9.5 billion in 10-year securities on
Wednesday and $9.5 billion Thursday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Feb. 4-5</NOTE>
