<HEAD>For release weekend editions Feb. 4-5</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: subpoenas went out.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures had a mixed week on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in March settled Friday at $4.30\ a bushel,
down from $4.40{ a week earlier; March corn was unchanged at $2.71}
a bushel; March oats advanced to $2.18} a bushel from $2.12; and
March soybeans rallied to $7.70{ a bushel from $7.54.
   Livestock and meat futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   February live cattle improved to 75.55 cents a pound from 73.40
cents; March feeder cattle rose to 84.65 cents a pound from 83.17;
February live hogs rallied to 44.02 cents a pound from 42.32 cents;
and February frozen pork bellies advanced to 40.82 cents a pound
from 38.60 cents.
   Gold and silver futures retreated for a second straight week on
New York's Commodity Exchange.
   April gold settled Friday at $396.30 a troy ounce compared with
$400.20 a week earlier; March silver fell to $5.875 from $6.245.
   Heating oil futures advanced but crude oil and gasoline slumped
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for March delivery fell to
$17.53 a barrel from $17.74; heating oil rose to 50.31 cents a
gallon from 49.88 cents; and March unleaded gasoline fell to 49.17
cents a gallon from 49.66 cents.
</TEXT>
